Between a Rock and  a Hard Place
Since the core cards are so low pointed you can kinda do whatever you want with the remaining 90 points.
Two big super mega ultra chickens. I'm really trying to cook here. Lemme know of any spicy suggestions especially for the side deck.

This is a Pure Tearlaments Deck. This is not a legal deck as many of the Tearlaments cards are either Restricted or Banned and this is purely made for entertainment purposes, duels with your friends, and otherwise "casual" play. This deck also does NOT contain any of the coveted "Ishizu" cards as it is built to be more on the "Pure" side by only contains cards from the Archetype Tearlaments and general support cards for the deck.

 

Keywords to Know (I do state them again multiple times throughout the description):

Mill/Milling = Sending the top X cards from your Deck to the Graveyard. (i.e. Mill or milling 3 means sending the top 3 cards from your Deck to the Graveyard)

"Ishizu" Cards = referring to the specific cards: Agido the Ancient Sentinel, Kelbek the Ancient Vanguard, Mudora the Sword Oracle, and Keldo the Sacred Protector.

Turn 0 = Your Opponent's First turn and the First Turn of the Duel.

Thin/Thinning = Removing cards from your Main Deck from (usually) search effects to make the Deck have less cards to have a more likely chance of drawing or milling the cards you want.

Fusion Summoning Effect = An effect shared by Tearlaments Havnis, Tearlaments Scheiren, and Tearlaments Merrli when they are sent to the Graveyard by card effect to Fusion Summon by shuffling themselves and other Fusion Material in the Hand, Field, or Graveyard into the bottom of the Deck/Extra Deck.

 

I'mma be honest. I have NO idea how to make this deck more casual. Maybe adding more weaker Fusion Monster you can Fusion into instead of "Meta Staples" or stronger generic cards. Because even as a "Pure" deck, this deck can be really consistent and can still get out full combo of its Main "Boss Monsters" onto the field. You could replace the more generic support cards in the Main Deck for more copies of the "in archetype" cards or perhaps other, weaker generic support cards. But nothing really comes in mind without abosuletly "bricking" this deck. Which in making a deck, casual or not, you still want it to be at least SOMEWHAT playable to have some fun. But I am open to suggestions if there are any :)

 

Again, I will be honest, this is mostly an essay and backstory of the deck, and overall review to myself of what I know about the deck so you can skip all of this if you want. :) I do continue with an explanation of deck after this monologue and tangent. I will state when the normal explanation starts in italics.

 

If you don't already know, Tearlaments is one of, if not, THE most powerful Deck in Yu-Gi-Oh! that needed multiple ban lists to make the Deck weaker and was one of the most skill intensive decks during its era; especially during the mirror match. I personally never played during this era, so I do not have the full context or knowledge of this deck. I just like the pretty looking cards.

The deck uses the Graveyard mechanic to its fullest potential, with each of the Main Deck Tearlaments cards having the same Fusion Summoning effects to bring out their Boss Monsters and other powerful utility Fusion Monsters like Predaplant Dragostapelia or Mudragon of the Swamp. It is also capable of going into other powerful Extra Deck monsters that even today in the modern age still see play or had to be banned because they were that good and stood the test of time. (See Abyss Dweller and Baronne de Fleur) What really made the deck go over the top in terms of how good it was with how consistent the deck truly was during its "Full Power" reign.

 

With the "Ishizu" cards; those being Agido the Ancient Sentinel, Kelbek the Ancient Vanguard, Keldo the Sacred Protector, and Mudora the Sword Oracle, bringing out its fullest potential. The deck truly could not be beat in terms of power, consistency, and speed and could not "brick." (open up a poor opening hand) If you weren't also playing Tearlaments during the time of its reign or specifically playing a deck that beat Tearlaments, you were almost always going to lose.

 

 

The deck was also unique in being able to play during "Turn 0" aka during your opponent's turn and being able to set up its own powerful board alongside the opponent. And the deck was just too fast that the Tearlaments player would probably already have a fully set up board and be able to interrupt your playings WHILE you were playing to set up your own board on YOUR TURN. They also had very little room for disruption as they could keep chaining their effects to each other, leaving very little breathing room and interaction windows for the opposing player to play against. Today, decks can now be seen also being able to play on their opponent's turn, but they still needed some form of starter or set up, so they can never have a "Turn 0" board and have a fully built board during the opponent's turn. (Decks like Dracotail can Fusion Summon on the opponent's turn and Labrynth can play a trap during the opponent's turn but not truly set up a full powered board from just a singular card WITHOUT even getting to their first official turn.)

Many more modern decks (at the time of writing this, January 2026) can now probably compete with Tearlaments in terms of power level and just how insanely broken and good decks have become. But this also could be attributed to how decks function nowadays and the power of individual cards as newer and more powerful cards are released to increase power-creep and get the people interested and entertained. With Kashtira and Maliss decks being almost full-blown counters to this deck as a whole as those decks mainly focus on Banishing as a mechanic.

In terms on "Unrestricted" or "Unlimited" formats, there are probably more powerful decks out there nowadays that can fully utilize all the power of some of the most overpowered cards to ever exist (Such as Painful Choice, Last Will, pre-errated Sangan and Witch of the Black Forest, Graceful Charity, and Pot of Greed) but even then, Tearlaments can still stand on its own without any of those cards. And with them, they can even add it to the deck for more power if needed.

 

 

Back to the regular explanation of the deck :D

 

 

Even as a "Pure" form of the deck, this deck is still insanely powerful. While not being as consistent without the "Ishizu" (Agido the Ancient Sentinel, Kelbek the Ancient Vanguard, Mudora the Sword Oracle, and Keldo the Sacred Protector) cards, it can still do a lot on its own and even with just only its current boss monsters. As stated before, the deck is a Graveyard and Fusion centered deck, with all the Main Deck Tearlaments cards having effects when they are sent to the Graveyard by card effect. And you accomplish this by using many of the Tearlaments card's "mill" effects (sending an X amount of cards from the top of your Deck to the Graveyard). The Main Deck Monsters also all having their own unique, powerful effects themselves, AND they all share a "Fusion Summoning Effect" when they are sent to the Graveyard by card effect; being able to Fusion Summon with materials in the Graveyard, field, or the hand. This means you are easily able to bring out the deck's 2 Main Boss Monsters without the need of a specific Fusion Spell like Polymerization. Not only that, but they will also shuffle themselves back to the bottom of the deck or Extra Deck when they Fusion Summon using this effect, so they never truly "leave play" as you will be able to either draw into them later or send them to the Graveyard again to activate their effects.

 

Tearlaments is a strong but very hard deck to learn and master as it is very skill intensive and it involves A LOT of interaction between you and your opponent. It involves you knowing what your cards do, when to activate them at optimal times, how they can react to each other as well, and of course your match-ups and overall knowledge of what your opponent's deck might do also help tremendiously.

 

 

An important sidenote I should say before getting into this is that all the Tearlaments Fusion Summoning effects are all ONCE PER TURN. So once you activate say Tearlaments Havnis' Fusion Summoning effect, if you mill her again, she CANNOT Fusion Summon again using her card effect.

 

Another important thing I will add is that your chaining order of effects is VERY important to mastering this deck. Usually, if you end up with a massive chain link, you want to chain Tearlaments Reinoheart first, your Tearlaments' Fusion Summoning effect secondly ( Tearlaments Merrli, Tearlaments Havnis, Tearlaments Scheiren; not in any specific order), your "Mill" effects third (Kelbek the Ancient Vanguard  and Agido the Ancient Sentinel if running Ishizu cards, Tearlaments Scream), and lastly, your search effects (Tearlaments Sulliek and Tearlaments Scream)

The search effects will help thin our deck out before you start milling, your mill effects can add more Fusion Material into the Graveyard, and then you can start to Fuse using all your materials in your Hand, Field, or (mainly) Graveyard. And lastly, Reinohart can send another Tearlament that has not triggered its Fusion Summoning effect to activate to Fusion Summon some more.

 

 

 

This will explain what the main cards do, you can skip this part and go onto the combo if you please.

 

For your Main cards, you have:

Tearlaments Reinoheart is what I like to think as your main starter, but can also act as an extender as for when summoned, he can send 1 Tearlaments Monster from your Deck to the Graveyard; immediately enabling you to Fusion Summon off of one Normal Summon. And, instead of sharing the Fusion Summon effect the other Tearlaments Monsters contain, he can instead Special Summon himself and send 1 Tearlaments card from your hand to the Graveyard. But the next time he leaves the field, he is banished. Which can be mitigated by using him in a Xyz Summon.
Tearlaments Merrli who can act as a starter for the deck. When she is summoned, she will "mill" (discard cards from the top of the deck to the Graveyard) the top 3 cards of your deck to the Graveyard. Allowing you to activate those "sent to Graveyard by card effect" effects and start chaining your Fusions and combos.
Tearlaments Scheiren can simply just Special Summon herself from your hand for free during your Main Phase which can also act as a starter. Which will also send a Monster (usually another Tearlaments) from your hand to the Graveyard. AND she also gets to mill 3.
And lastly, Tearlaments Havnis, which is the card that truly allows you to play during "Turn 0" by herself. She can Special Summon herself out from your hand whenever your opponent activates ANY Monster effect on the field. AND she will also mill 3.

 

 

Other notable Main Deck cards are:

Primeval Planet Perlereino is also a starter which as it can add 1 Tearlaments Monster from your Deck to your hand. It also has 2 bonus effects. One being an attack boost to all Tearlaments AND Fusion Monsters you control. And the second, which activates whenever a Tearlaments Monster you control OR in the Graveyard is shuffled into the Deck or Extra Deck, can target and destroy 1 card on the field.
Tearlaments Scream is a powerful utility card which has 2 effects; one on the field when played as normal and one when sent to the Graveyard by card effect. The first, allowing you to mill an additional 3 whenever ANY Monster is Normal or Special Summoned if you control a Tearlaments Monster and it has the bonus effect that Monster your opponent controls lose 500 ATK. And second, you can add 1 Tearlaments Trap from your Deck to your hand when this card is sent to the Graveyard by card effect.
And speaking of Tearlaments Traps, Tearlaments Sulliek has 2 effects of its own; one on the field and one when sent to the Graveyard. The first can be activated if you control a Tearlaments Monster to target an Effect Monster your opponent controls, negate its effects, and then send 1 Monster you control to the Graveyard. And second, if this card is sent to the Graveyard by card effect, you can add 1 Tearlaments Monster from your Deck to your hand.
Lastly, the last notable card I will speak of in the Main Deck is Tearlaments Cryme. It is an "In Archetype" Counter Trap card that can be activated when you control a Tearlaments monster to negate the activation of a Monster effect, Spell, or Trap that is activated and shuffle it into the Deck. Then, you send 1 Monster from your hand to the Graveyard. Additionally, it also has an effect when it is sent to the Graveyard by card effect to target 1 banished Tearlaments monster and to add it to your hand.

 

Lastly, the Extra Deck Tearlaments Monsters, of which there are 3 which are:

Tearlaments Kitkallos, a key piece of the Tearlaments Deck. If it is Special Summoned, it can either add or send 1 Tearlaments card from your Deck to the hand or Graveyard, respectively. It also has the activated effect to target 1 Monster you control (She can target herself too, yes), Special Summon 1 Tearlaments Monster from your hand or Graveyard, and then send the targeted card to the Graveyard. And if Kitakallos is sent to the Graveyard by card effect, she can mill 5 instead.
Tearlaments Rulkallos  is one of the 2 Main "Boss Monsters" of the Deck. She has the passive effect that other Aqua Monsters you control cannot be destroyed by Battle. And when your opponent activates a card or effect that includes an effect to Special Summon Monster(s), she can negate the activation, destroy it, and then send 1 Tearlaments card from your hand or field to the Graveyard. And if this Fusion Summoned card is sent to the Graveyard by card effect, she can Special Summon herself back out. (Meaning, if she uses this effect to revive herself, and she is then sent to the Graveyard again by card effect again, she cannot Special Summon herself from the Graveyard again.)
And lastly, the secondly Main "Boss Monster", Tearlaments Kaleido-Heart. If he is Special Summoned, or an Aqua Monster is sent to the Graveyard by card effect, you can target 1 card your opponent controls, and shuffle it into the Deck. And he shares the effect that if this Fusion Summoned card is sent to Graveyard by card effect, he can Special Summon himself back, and then you send 1 Tearlaments card from your Deck to the Graveyard.

 

So all in all, a lot of powerful cards with just these card's Archetype alone. 

 

 

 

As for combos, this deck has a lot and a lot of potential plays to go into. And truly, there is no 1 specific "board state" to end up with. Most of this deck ends up with "What if" situations and just knowing your best options at certain times is the most important. But I will give 1 sample combo I know (which might not be the most optimial but I will try my best)

 

A sample combo for this deck is (Tearlaments Reinoheart  in hand):

Normal Summon Tearlaments Reinoheart. Activate his effect to send Tearlaments Havnis (or the other 2, Tearlaments Merrli and Tearlaments Scheiren. Just know you will have to change targets for whenever I say their names next) from Deck to grave. Activate Tearlaments Havnis' effect in grave to Fusion Summon into Tearlaments Kitkallos. Tearlaments Kitkallos effect on summon to add Tearlaments Merrli from Deck to hand. Activate Tearlaments Kitkallos' second effect to target and send herself to the Graveyard to Special Summon Merrli from your hand. Chain Link 1 Kitkallos Chain Link 2 Merrli. Tearlaments Merrli will Mill 3, and Tearlaments Kitkallos will Mill 5, milling 8 cards in total. (If Tearlaments Scream is activated, you can mill an additional 3 to mill 11 cards in total. With the "Ishizu" cards, this makes it even more consistent as the deck can mill EVEN MORE, up to 10 with 5 each if Agido the Ancient Sentinel and Kelbek the Ancient Vanguard are milled.)

Assumingly, you will mill a Tearlaments Monster that is not a Tearlaments we already sent to the Graveyard. In this instance, we already sent Tearlaments Havnis to the grave. And in this instance, let's assume we get a hit and mill a Tearlaments Scheiren.

Activate Tearlaments Scheiren's effect to Fusion Summon using herself and Tearlaments Kitkallos in the Graveyard to summon (usually) Tearlaments Rulkallos.

 

Now, a lot of siutations after this are a bunch of "what if..." situations. But with how consistent this deck is, and the fact that we just milled 8 cards out of our 40(3) card deck, 5 of which we drew to start; it is very likely you get another card you can activate in the Graveyard. If you milled another Tearlaments Reinoheart, you can Special Summon him and then send 1 Tearlaments card you might have in your hand which can then also activate its effect. Maybe you milled another Tearlaments Merrli which you can then Fusion Summon with a Reinohart you might have in the grave or hand as well. Or you have a Tearlaments Scheiren in your hand to Special Summon to mill even more. Or you milled one of the Spell or Traps that can add a Tearlaments or send a Tearlaments to the grave. It is a lot of "What ifs".

 

Again, I reiterate that there is no specific "End Board" for this deck. It is based on wha you might end up with, what you might need, or what else you could have done as there is still a bunch of cards probably in your hand you can play, in your grave, or still waiting in your Main Deck.

 

For this End Board, we at least have a Tearlaments Rulkallos which by herself may not seem like much, but she is a VERY strong card so she is not to be underestimated as she has her negate AND can extend your plays during YOUR OPPONENT'S TURN to send a Tearlaments card to the Graveyard and Fusion Summon during THEIR turn.

 

 

 

 

Overall, this is an extremely powerful and fun deck, even in its "Pure" form. Lots of plays can be made and it still has a lot of consistency by itself. I know this is a lot of yapping but I wish you the best of luck in mastering this "Tier 0", best of the best decks. I hope you enjoy! :)

 

 

 



P.S. I had to rewrite this TWICE because the website kept crashing on me :<

deck_description: The culmination of sunk cost falacy (30$ on Hecahands cards)

This is my personal build of the Blue-Eyes White Dragon for 2026. As with many other varients of the Blue-Eyes structure deck, this deck can be assmebled with just three structure decks.

 

The deck is designed to learn how to play "Blue-Eyes" and understand the different combo lines. It's also quite budget friendly, being right under $15.00 for the entire deck.

 

If you check out Jesse Kotton and TSX1's Blue-Eye budget decks, you'll find many similarities to mine with a few exceptions. I included Destined Rivals, the White Stone of Ancients, The Ultimate Creature of Destruction, three Tyrant Dragons, two Neo Blue-Eyes, and Indigo Eyes.

 

At the end of the day, the decks are more so for fun at home or at locals. Still, if you learn the decks at its most basic level, then you'll be able to properly add other cards to increase the deck's celling.

So this is an updated varient to my Blue-Eyes deck. While the previous deck stuck with just the contents inside the structure deck, this version requires cards outside of it. Despite costing a bit more, this version could be considered a budget friendly build, costing less than $20.

 

Most decks involve the primite cards but since they're signifigantly more expensive, I decided to go an alternate route that involves the metalmorph package. I've also included both the Crimson Dragon engine along with Jet dragon.

 

I wouldn't say this deck is anywhere near "Meta-level" but I'd be willing to bring this deck to locals with a high chance of winning.

This is your typical competitive Blue-Eyes Primite deck. For the most part, the common core of Blue-Eyes and Primite cards are included. 

 

The addition to Blue-Eyes Jet Dragon was to help give the deck an extra interuption and a body without clogging the deck up.

I cut out 1 copy of "Wishes for Eyes of Blue" because outside of using it in your opening hand, you'll often add this card off of the effect of "True Light".

Primite Roar is added to give you an extra chance to draw out Blue-Eyes

Pot of Prospertiy is there to help dig into your deck for your starters

Synchro Rumble and the Crimson Dragon package are also present

We've included Dominus Purge because the only attributes you use are Earth and Light, keeping you unaffected by the downside of the card.

The many regionals across the world have ended and the results are in. Joey Wheeler won Domino City, Quattro won Heartland after his opponent was disqualified, and The Sledgehammer won Paradise City after the disappearance of Yusho Sakaki during the finals. deck_excerpt: Did you know that Branded Dracotail is the current #1 ladder strategy according to Masterduelmeta?
deck_description:
Did you know that Branded Dracotail is the current #1 ladder strategy according to Masterduelmeta? With this incredible power, it's time to tear apart ladder with Albaz and his newfound friends! (I speak from personal experience, this is the deck I used to reach Masters 1 this season).

These spellcaster dragons do relatively few actions for a lot of impact! Everytime you fusion summon with Dracotail monsters, can set a Dracotail spell/trap from deck, then get an additional effect which breaks your opponent's board, giving this strategy inherent board breaking capabilities. Dracotail Faimena can also fusion summon as a quick effect during the Main Phase, meaning you can fusion summon turn 0 and immediately start interrupting your opponent! This low amount of special summons Dracotail does allows it to perfectly play in Maxx "C," creating a lot of advantage and interruptions while minimizing the amount of draws your opponent gets. 

Paired with Branded, Dracotail becomes near unstoppable! Phryxul is the perfect card to bridge both Branded and Dracotail decks! Phryxul is the perfect card to bridge both Branded and Dracotail decks! This strategy generates a ton of massive beatsticks on field, smashes through established boards with in-engine cards, and generates a ton of advantage! Albax and Phryxul has truly made the ultimate fusion strategy!

GLHF Duelists! 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: This is a Pure Red-Eyes Black Dragon Deck.
deck_description:
This is a Pure Red-Eyes Black Dragon made for casual and fun play. This deck is not meant to be good or competitive in any way. This deck is purely made for fun.

First off, the deck is not good AT ALL. This is a SUPER CASUAL Deck meant to be used in friendly and casual Duels. Red-Eyes has such terrible support cards and gets almost no attention compared to Blue-Eyes. For Red-Eyes, the deck CAN have many different strategies, but it's not particularly good at any of the strategies it has access to, with the main and better of them all probably being the Red-Eyes Burn deck with all the burn cards the deck has access to like Inferno Fire Blast and Red-Eyes Burn. 
"Jack of All Trades, Master of None"
If you want to make the deck better, you can add the Primite engine with Primite Dragon Ether Beryl and its fusion card Primite Dragon Nether Berzelius or use the very strong Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon that is in this deck. I've also seen some strategies involving Red-Eyes Metal Claws Dragon and Red-Eyes Black Fullmetal Dragon with Max Metalmorph floating around as well. But I personally have no idea how they work, as I have not touched any Red-Eyes deck in years. 

For this deck's main strategy, it is a "Beat Down" strategy meant to bring a bunch of Red-Eyes Black Dragons onto the field and attack your opponent for a lot of damage. This deck was mainly brought from a VERY old Duel Links deck I used to have that was actually one of the very first decks I ever made and came up with. And in Duel Links, Red-Eyes Beat Down during the time was actually somewhat viable as combos were almost non-existent and the Lifepoint total being so low meant that Beat Down strategies were pretty good. 

I won't really be providing a combo for this deck, as there really isn't one? You bring out Red-Eyes Black Dragon, maybe fuse into Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon or Red-Eyes Slash Dragon for more "unga bunga", and use Return of the Red-Eyes and Red-Eyes Spirit to bring Red-Eyes back from the Graveyard. That's about it.
But alas, I will TRY to maybe provide a "combo" if you can call it that. 

The "Combo" (Red-Eyes Insight in hand):
Activate Red-Eyes Insight sending Red-Eyes Black Dragon from the Deck to the Graveyard and add Red-Eyes Fusion to your hand. Activate Red-Eyes Fusion to Fusion Summon either Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon or Red-Eyes Slash Dragon. Set whatever traps you may have. PaSs. 

Again, VERY casual deck. Most cards will send a "Red-Eyes" monster to the Graveyard which you can bring back with many of your Trap Cards' effects and most of the "good" Red-Eyes cards will use "burn" strategies.
And a lot of the older cards depend on your opponent either attacking into them or doing something, so it's more so for very casual and slow paced Duels.

 

Overall still, this deck can be very fun in very casual Duel and settings with your friends and even has an OP Boss Monster you can go into (Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon) which you always swap out if you want to be more casual. I hope you enjoy!

deck_excerpt: A more or less Pure Dracotail Deck.
deck_description:
This is a more or less Pure Dracotail Deck. This deck is not meant to be particularly good or "meta" and is made with the intention of more casual and fun duels while still being somewhat competent and playable. 

The Main Deck contains a Bystial Engine for now, as I could not really think of a more "casual" engine or cards to add into the deck without just running a bunch of Monster Hand-Traps into the deck or adding a bunch of cards that would otherwise completely "brick" the deck. But maybe you can find other Monsters to shove into the deck to use for Fusions and support to make the deck better, such as maybe a better engine or, as I said, running more hand-traps.  

For the Extra Deck, most of the cards added are Dragon Fusion Monsters the deck can fuse into, as well as some generic Link Monsters to link into. 

For the Side Deck, I added Fallen of Albaz, Chamber Dragonmaid, Blaster, Dragon Ruler of Infernos, El Shaddoll Winda, and Primite Dragon Ether Beryl as stand-ins for the Branded, Dragonmaid, Dragon Ruler, Shaddoll, and Primite engines respectively for consideration. With the better of them all being the Branded, Dragonmaid, and Shaddoll decks in my opinion. The Side Deck also contains some generic Dragon support cards, and I wish I could have added more Spellcaster support cards as well, or more "casual" cards to add into the deck.

 

Dracotail is an insanely powerful deck whose main goal is to Fusion Summon into its powerful Boss Monsters as well as other very power Fusion Dragon and Spellcaster Monsters. The deck mainly wants a lot of Monster cards in the deck in order to use as material for their Fusion Summons. The deck is very consistent and can run other engines in order to make it even more consistent, fuse into other powerful Monsters, or extend the capabilities of the deck. Or it can even instead run a bunch of hand-traps instead like Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring; the Mulcharmies those being Mulcharmy Fuwalos, Mulcharmy Purulia, and Mulcharmy Meowls; and Effect Veiler. The deck is also able to fuse during the opponent's turn with the help of Dracotail Faimena and set-up some interruptions. The deck being as flexible as it is, being able to be run in many different strategies, as well as having its own powerful cards is why at the time of writing this, (Jaunary 2026) it is one of the most successful decks out there currently. 
I think the most important part of mastering this deck is knowing how to use the many disruptions you may have access to with this deck, as well as which disruptions to use against a specific match-up, or when to use your disruptions. Knowing your match-ups, your opponent's deck, overall game knowledge, and how to use and get into your big plays make or break this deck as a whole.

 

As for this particular deck, the main goal is to fuse into Dracotail Arthalion and Dracotail Gulamel for their powerful effects and recursion in order to interrupt your opponent's plays and set up your own powerful board.

A sample combo for this deck is as follows (Dracotail Lukias + 1 other Monster in hand): 
Normal Summon Dracotail Lukias. Activate her effect to add Dracotail Faimena from your Deck to your hand. Activate Dracotail Faimena in hand, discarding herself to Fusion Summon using Dracotail Lukias + the 1 other Monster in hand to Fusion Summon Dracotail Arthalion. Chain 1 Arthalion, chain 2 Lukias. Dracotail Lukias will set from your Deck to the field Rahu Dracotail. Dracotail Arthalion on Fusion Summon will add Dracotail Faimena back into your hand from the grave. Activate Rahu Dracotail to Fusion Summon using Dracotail Faimena in hand and Dracotail Urgula from the deck to Fusion Summon into Dracotail Gulamel. Chain both Dracotail Faimena  and Dracotail Urgula to set Dracotail Horn and Dracotail Flame. Activate Dracotail Urgula in grave to shuffle himself to the bottom of the Deck to add Dracotail Faimena from grave to hand. Pass.

This board consists of Dracotail Faimena in hand to Fusion Summon during your opponent's Main Phase, Dracotail Gulamel upon the activation of ANY Dracotail card or effect to 1 card your opponent controls and destroy it, and both set traps Dracotail Horn to target an Attack Position Monster on the field, return it to the hand or Extra Deck; and Dracotail Flame to target 1 face-up Spell, negate its effects until the end of the turn; and both allow you to shuffle 1 Dracotail card from the Graveyard or banishment to the bottom of the Deck, and Draw 1 card.
Additionally, both Dracotail Arthalion and Dracotail Gulamel have recursion effects while they are in the Graveyard to Special Summon themselves from the Graveyard whenever 2 or more monsters are sent to the Graveyard, but they will get banished if they leave the field. 
Dracotail Faimena can Fusion Summon into a lot of disruptive options such as another Dracotail Arthalion which can "bounce" more Monsters on the field and/or Graveyard to the hand, up to the amount of Fusion Material that was used in your hand; Secreterion Dragon to use as a floodgate against other Dragon/Spellcaster decks if you know what your opponent is using; Mysterion the Dragon Crown which can banish Monsters that Special Summon themselves or Monsters with its same original Type, and then banish all Monsters on the field with its same original Type; Filia Regis which can banish a card your opponent controls or in their Graveyard; or Khaos Starsource Dragon which can target and destroy cards your opponent controls, up to the number of Light and Dark Monsters used for Fusion Material.
Lastly, if you Fusion Summon using one of your Main Deck Dracotail Monsters, all the Main Deck Dracotail Monsters share the same secondary effect to Set 1 Dracotail Spell or Trap from the Deck to the field in order to add more follow-up or disruption during your next turn.

 

Overall, a very fun and powerful deck which a lot of flexibility, lots of potential, and lots of things it is able to play. I hope you enjoy!

deck_name: Pure Azamina (Fusion x Synchro Festival+ January 2026)
deck_excerpt: Fusions or Synchros? Why not both?
deck_description:
Some tips

Dramatic Snake-Eye Chase is a replacement for the event limited Deception of the Sinful Spoils. Dramatic Snake-Eye Chase can place a Diabellstar the Black Witch or Diabellstar Vengeance from your hand, deck, or graveyard face-up in your spell and trap zone as a continuous spell, then its graveyard effect can banish itself from your graveyard during the end phase to special summon that monster. In short, it's better than nothing to start a play.

Diabellstar Vengeance is always treated as a Sinful Spoils card, so you can use her as fusion material for your Azamina cards. This effect is still live even if you place Diabellstar Vengeance face-up on your field with the effect of Dramatic Snake-Eye Chase.

Diabellstar Vengeance can also special summon Poplar of the White Forest and Silvera, Wolf Tamer of the White Forest from your extra deck with her destruction effect if another Diabell monster card is on the field. Poplar can synchro summon on your opponent's turn. Silvera can flip all of your opponent's monsters face-down if she's special summoned.

deck_name: star warrior fiedsmith engine master duel

deck_description:
Well, here’s to hoping that Herald of the Arc Light stays at 1 on the next banlist so that I can continue making Prediction Princess Decks (but it’s probably not surviving).

Assault Sonic Warrior is the last monster retrain for the Junk Warrior Support that references Jack and Yusei’s final duel in 5D’s, and it is a great card. While it technically also is Support for Assault Mode, I feel like that part of it is only useful for allowing it to be able to be searched off of Duel Evolution - Assault Zone and Crimson Blade/Assault Mode. As for how it changes Synchron Prediction Princess, you don’t have to play either Assault Synchron or Satellite Synchron for Level 2 extenders. But because of that, we can cut those and the copies of Tuning from my previous list and just throw in 3 Assault Sonic Warriors and more non-engine, which is great. 

Full combo is either Full-Speed Warrior and a discard or Assault Sonic Warrior and a discard. By extension, that also means that Reinforcement of the Army and a discard or Synchro Fellowship and a discard is full combo. Let’s say that you have Assault Sonic Warrior. Normal Summon it and activate its effect on Normal Summon to search for Scrap Synchron. Synchro Scrap Synchron in hand and Assault Sonic Warrior on field into Scrap Warrior. Chain Link 1 Scrap Warrior’s effect on Synchro Summon and Chain Link 2 Assault Sonic Warrior’s effect to boost all monsters you control by 500 ATK since it was sent to GY as Synchro Material. Scrap Warrior adds Synchro Fellowship from Deck to hand. Activate Synchro Fellowship to search for another Assault Sonic Warrior and a Junk Synchron, sending a card from hand to GY. Activate Synchro Fellowship’s effect in GY, banishing it to reduce Scrap Warrior’s Level by 1 and giving you an additional Normal Summon of a Synchron monster during this Main Phase. Normal Summon Junk Synchron and activate its effect targeting and Special Summoning Assault Sonic Warrior back from the GY. Because you control a card that mentions Junk Warrior, you can activate Assault Sonic Warrior’s effect in hand to Special Summon itself. Synchro Junk Synchron and any Level 2 monster into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar who searches for World Legacy Monstrosity from Deck. Synchro the Level 5 Ib, and the other 2 Level 2 monsters you have (either 2 Assault Sonic Warriors or 1 Assault Sonic Warrior and Scrap Warrior whose Level was reduced by 1) into Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys. Crocodragon activates on Synchro Summon to draw 2 cards because it used 2 non-Tuners as material. Activate Monstrosity targeting Crocodragon to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Enneacraft - Asta.PIXEA from Deck. Xyz PIXEA and Crocodragon into Mereologic Aggregator in the EMZ and on Xyz Summon it sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY. Herald triggers to search for Prediction Princess Tarotrei. Activate Aggregator’s other effect targeting Herald in GY, detaching 1 Xyz Material, and then attaching Herald from GY to itself. Link Aggregator into Gravity Controller. This triggers Herald as it was sent to GY again which gives you a search for Underworld Ritual of Prediction. Activate Underworld Ritual to Ritual Summon Tarotrei by tributing Bibliomuse. Bibliomuse triggers in GY off of being tributed in order to Special Summon herself back face-down. Activate Tarotrei’s effect targeting Bibliomuse to flip it face-up, which triggers its Flip Effect to add Prediction Princess Tarotreith and another Underworld Ritual from Deck. Activate Underworld Ritual tributing Bibliomuse to Ritual Summon Tarotreith face-down. During your End Phase, activate Tarotrei’s effect in order to Special Summon PIXEA back from the GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, you can banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon a Bibliomuse from Deck face-down and chain Tarotrei’s effect targeting your face-down Tarotreith to flip it face-up. On a new chain, Tarotreith’s Flip Effect triggers to Special Summon a Deus-X Krawler from Deck face-down. On another new chain, you can then Quick Effect activate Tarotreith’s other effect to flip Bibliomuse, Deus-X, and PIXEA face-up. Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect searches a Prediction Princess monster and a Ritual Spell for follow-up and she provides your Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. Deus-X, after it is flipped face-up, negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field. PIXEA, after it is flipped face-up, prevents your opponent from targeting cards on the field or in either GY with card effects. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Enneacraft - Asta.PIXEA which can, when your opponent activates a card or effect that targets a card(s) you control, flip itself face-up as part of this effect’s activation in order to negate that effect and then allow you to banish a random card out of your opponent’s hand face-down. Also, after it has been flipped face-up, your opponent cannot target cards on either field or in either GY with card effects. 1 Turbo-Tainted Hot Rod GT19 which is a Level 3 Flip Tuner whose Flip Effect allows you to declare a Level from 1 to 9 and have it become that Level until the end of the turn. Also, after it has been flipped face-up, it can Quick Effect target 1 other face-up monster on either field to Quick Synchro with that monster, but you can only use 1 effect per turn and only once that turn. You don’t need to play this card. I was going to use this list in a guide on the best Synchro Monsters to make with Hot Rod in Prediction Princess, but whether or not that actually happens depends on whether or not Herald of the Arc Light gets banned on the next list. You can play a Called by the Grave instead of this card. 2 Junk Synchron which on Normal Summon can target a Level 2 or lower monster in your GY and Special Summon it with its effects negated. Realistically, you only need 1, but because you don’t want to draw it in order to use Synchro Fellowship, we are playing 2. However, that comes out to be quite nice as it can allow for follow-up Synchro plays. 3 Full-Speed Warrior which adds Junk Synchron or a Spell/Trap that mentions Junk Warrior from your Deck to your hand. 3 Assault Sonic Warrior. If you control Junk Warrior or Assault Mode Activate or a card that mentions either, you can Special Summon it from hand and if it is Normal or Special Summoned, you can add a Synchron monster or an AMA from Deck to hand. Also, if it is sent to GY as Synchro Material, your monsters gain 500 ATK for the turn. We are not playing Duel Evolution - Assault Zone or Crimson Blader/Assault Mode to search this card because we already have 10 cards in our Main Deck that get us to full combo. That’s 1/4 of the Deck, so it would be better to play non-engine than even more searchers. Also, its last effect can be used to Chain Block Scrap Warrior’s effect, which is nice. 1 Scrap Synchron which can be used as Synchro Material from hand if you Synchro Summon a monster that mentions a Synchron Tuner as material and it can substitute itself for any Synchron Tuner for the Synchro Summon of a monster. 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, and 3 Droll & Lock Bird. 

For Spell/Traps: 1 Reinforcement of the Army which can search either Assault Sonic Warrior or Full-Speed Warrior. 1 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. 3 Synchro Fellows which adds a Junk Synchron and a monster that mentions Junk Warrior from your Deck to your hand and then you discard a card. You can also banish it from GY and target a Synchro Monster you control to decrease that monster’s Level by 1 and then give yourself another Normal Summon of a Synchron monster in addition to your Normal Summon/Set this turn. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 3 Infinite Impermanence. 1 World Legacy Pawns which is an alternative search off of Ib if you already drew Monstrosity and it simply just targets a face-down monster you control and changes it to face-up Attack or Defense Position. 

Extra Deck: 1 Elder Entity N’tss which can target and destroy a card on field when it is sent to the GY. For the Synchro Monsters that we are playing specifically for Turbo-Tainted Hot Rod GT19, we have Snake-Eyes Vengeance Dragon, Chaos Angel, and F.A. Dawn Dragster. But, if you don’t want to play Hot Rod, Vengeance Dragon is still good to keep in the Extra Deck to possibly Synchro a Junk Synchron and a Level 9 monster on a following turn for some clean-up. The same can be said for Chaos Angel as Normal Summon Junk Synchron, bring back Scrap Synchron, and Synchroing Scrap Synchron with either Tarotrei or Tarotreith can make Chaos Angel. But, that is a bit more work, so I’d probably just play Vengeance Dragon. 1 Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys which draws you cards when it is Synchro Summoned equal to the number of non-Tuners used for its Synchro Summon. Also, you can Quick Effect discard 2 cards to target and destroy a card on field. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar who searches for a World Legacy card on Synchro Summon. 1 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck to hand when it is sent to GY. 1 Scrap Warrior which searches takes a Junk Synchron or a card that mentions Junk Warrior from your Deck and either adds it to hand or sends it to GY on Synchro Summon. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Dyna Mondo. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 Gravity Controller. 

Side Deck: 3 Dinowrestler Pankratops, 3 Mulcharmy Purulia, 3 Dark Ruler No More, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, 1 Triple Tactics Talent, 3 Evenly Matched, and 1 Solemn Judgment.

deck_name: Branded Dracotail (Fusion x Synchro Festival+ January 2026)

deck_description: Just trying something to take for a spin.

A budget Pure Blue-Eyes deck for the Genesys format:

- Deck does well going first. Most turn 1 boards will be 2x Spirit Dragon, 1x True Light, one or two spell/trap disruptions (and sometimes a veiler in hand), and a Blue-Eyes Jet Dragon on the field if you are lucky. On average 4-5 disruptions/negates for your turn 1 board. Going second is trickier, so either hope to draw into hand traps or side deck Dark Ruler No More/Ultimate Slayer etc.

- Side deck is budget and meta-dependent.

- Neo-Kaiser Seahorse added as a quick and easy way to get out Snake-Eyes Vengeance Dragon, along with another way of targeting Maiden of White for the extra tuner/BEWD summon from the GY.

- You want to create 2x Spirit Dragon if possible, due to the toolbox of light synchro dragons you can tag into during opponent's turn. Note that opening with Maiden as the only starter will only yield 1x Spirit Dragon, but opening with Maiden + Neo-Kaiser Seahorse can yield 1x Spirit Dragon and 1x Snake-Eyes Vengeance Dragon. Also, opening with Maiden + Mausoleum will yield 2x Spirit Dragon (hence the inclusion of 3x Mausoleum).

- 3x White Stone of Ancients added as an easy discard target for Wishes, enabling board protection through an end of turn summoning of Blue-Eyes Jet Dragon from the deck. Can cut to 1x to add other hand traps if needed.

- 2x Blue-Eyes Jet Dragon (rather than 1x) added for greater consistency of White Stone of Ancients summoning Jet Dragon from the Deck (in case we open with Jet Dragon in hand). Can do with 1x Jet Dragon if you want to add other hand traps.

- 3x Primite Drillbeam is a superb and budget negate that works well with the deck even without the rest of the Primite Package.

- Ether Beryl not added, as the deck no longer has a consistent access to 2x normal summons (due to no Spirit with Eyes of Blue link monster), and having more options in your synchro/fusion/xyz toolbox seems better than adding extra summon enablers like Ancient Fairy Dragon. Kaibaman the Legend also not added for the same reason as Ether Beryl.

- 2x Wishes (rather than 1x) is optional, but having 2x Wishes allows for Bingo Machine to be a pseudo-starter (2/3 chance rather than just 1/3 chance of grabbing Wishes). This approach actually works considerably consistently, allowing the deck to have a total of 14 "starters" - going first, 8 of these (Sage, Piri, Wishes) yield 2x Spirit Dragon, 3 of these (Maidens) yield 1x Spirit Dragon and another Spirit Dragon/Vengeance Dragon if paired with Mausoleum/Neo-Kaiser Seahorse, and 3 (Bingo Machine) have a 2/3 chance of adding Wishes, or grabbing a Roar/Majesty/Destined Rivals/Jet Dragon.

deck_excerpt: A simple deck that changes the midrange WelleDad strategy by focusing on quickly summoning multiple Synchro monsters
deck_description: A simple deck that changes the midrange WelleDad strategy by focusing on quickly summoning multiple Synchro monsters to gain an early advantage.

Updated my build of Pure Harpies after the Feb 2, 2026 banlist and finally decided to start posting it to this site. We lost Harpie's Feather Storm, which was our main meta-relevant card, so the deck is substantially worse now. Until we get more support that doesn't make us go negative, this build is what has been working best for me. This deck loses to handtraps, so hopefully you draw well enough to bait one out. I do not consider this archetype competitive, but unfortunately I am attached to it since I have been playing it since 2013 so I keep trying to make it viable.

Harpie core is pretty standard, 3x Harpie Lady, 3x Channeler, 3x Perfumer, 3x Fire Blast, 3x Hysteric Sign are all mandatory in my opinion. 1-2x Harpist, 1x queen and 1x Oracle round out a few more names. 1x Hunting Grounds, 1x Feather Rest, 1x Feather Duster since they are searchable off of Sign. Alluring Mirror Split is debatable, but has been reasonable good for me and can be your secondary search off of Perfumer. You can run 2 or 3 Egotist. I like 3 because it is a card I prefer to see in my opening hand more often than not.

Channeller and Perfumer are your main normal summons. If they get negated hopefully you drew an extender. If you can bait out the interaction before resolving your Channeler and Perfumer effects that will give you the best chance to succeed.

Using 2x Swallow's Cowrie to improve consistency on getting the Harpie we need, but it is debatable. Haven't found a better option, and this is more efficient that Small World in Pure Harpies. 2x Unexpected Dai, free summon of a normal Harpie with minimal restrictions. Unexpected Dai plus an extender will get you to most of the extra deck.

1x Tempest is in there because mostly because I like it, but it does give us some recursion that isn't terrible and it can search Fire Blast while setting itself up in grave. Replaceable, but I do like it.

3x Forbidden Droplet as interaction, battle damage, and as an outlet to dump Hysteric Sign since this deck hemorrhages resources. I consider 3x to be mandatory, does a lot for the deck besides just a strong negation. You want to see this card.

3x Imperm because it has been the most consistently useful handtrap for me. Really strong. Side it out for more relevant handtraps depending on matchup.

1x Talent and 1x Called By, 1-of power cards.

1x Double Or Nothing! Absolute brick, card sucks. You do not want to draw this, you only want to search it off of Utopia Double. Allows you to swing for 10,000 with the Utopia Double setup.

I am not running Hysteric Party, not searchable, too slow, too vulnerable, and requires a discard. Can potentially give you a sacky big play, but it has almost always been irrelevant for me the last few years.

Extra Deck is flexible. I am also using the Utopia Double package again. I am not a huge fan of the Utopia Double package because it adds a brick, but with Feather Storm gone we need a way to win, and I have had some success with this package in this build of the deck. Very glass cannon and quite frankly it sucks, but it does give you a way to win a game with minimal resources and you would be surprised how often this steals games. The Accesscode Talker setup is pretty nice to have, and the Spiders allow for maximizing value of normal harpies. Harpie's Phantasmal can just about win games on it's own. 2x cyber slash because they are easy to make and are disruptive. You can also go with toolbox rank 4's like Chidori or Giant Hand.

The side deck I currently have is generic. Tune it for the meta you expect to play against. Gardala is there because it is a Wind and a kaiju. Little Knight, Chidori, and a second Hunting Ground are there when I side out the Utopia Double Package.

Long story short, deck bad and I still love it.
Maybe this deck could be good against the meta post banlist

deck_description: Im curious about the new pendulum archetype
Archfiend deck post tcg release of Burst Protocol

Yummy took some big hits in the pre-BPRO banlist, but Mimighoul is here to ruin your opponen'ts day!

Mimighoul Maker is your ideal 1-card combo. Start off by activating it, revealing Mimighoul Dragon and Mimighoul Archfiend. This combo goes one of two ways depending on what your opponent picks here.

Ideally, they'll pick Dragon, which will go face-down on their field, meaning you'll get to special summon Archfiend from your hand, forcing the Dragon face-up. This will activate its effect, and switch control back to you. (FUN FACT: This makes both Triple Tactics cards live, so you can use them any time after this. Ideal shot is Triple Tactics Thrust to search The Black Goat Laughs.) Next, link off either of your monsters into Linkuriboh and synchro it and the other monster into CupsyYummy Way, using it to search for CupsyYummy and MarshmaoYummy, discarding the Marshmao.

Next up, Link off your Cupsy Way into YummySnatchy, using its effect to place the YummyusmentAcroquey field spell on your field. after this, special summon your Cupsy, use its effect to search for YummySurprise, and Synchro the two monsters into LollipoYummy Way, special summoning Marshmao and Cupsy from your GY. Use these two to Xyz summon Giant Mimighoul, and use its effect to search for Mimighoul Dungeon (if you already have it in hand, search for Mimighoul Room instead). Activate this and use it to search for Mimighoul Fairy, which you can special summon face-down to your opponent's field. Thanks to Dungeon, they won't be able to normal summon, or attack with monsters special summoned this turn, until they flip it up, locking themselves out of monster effects in the hand. Lastly, set your Surprise, and Room if you have it, and pass turn.

During your opponent's turn, once they've flipped the Fairy, you'll want to wait until they have a breakable board before activating Room, as your only target will be the other copy of Dragon, and if Dungeon is still on your field, they'll be forced to flip it if they want to attack you this turn. Also, you can use Suprise to put Acroquey back in your field zone once they've flipped up Fairy, so you can get some extra pops when you quick synchro your Yummys.

Alternatively, if they pick the Archfiend, they take it face-down, and you get the Dragon, and you'll special summon it as part of Maker's effect. Dragon will search for Dungeon, which you'll activate and search Fairy with. You'll be able to special summon Fairy from your hand, and link one of them off into Linkuriboh, and get into combo from there. You'll lose out on the Fairy lock, but you'll get a free draw, and your opponent will have to discard a card once Archfiend flips up.

Primite Harpies after the Feb 2, 2026 banlist. We lost Harpie's Feather Storm, which was our main meta-relevant card, so the deck is substantially worse now and I think a Primite engine works pretty well to give us back a bit of control. My pure build is still what I prefer, but that may just be nostalgia.

Harpie core is pretty standard, 3x Harpie Lady, 3x Channeler, 3x Perfumer, 3x Fire Blast, 3x Hysteric Sign are all mandatory in my opinion. 1x Harpist, 1x queen and 1x Oracle round out a few more names. 1x Hunting Grounds, 1x Feather Rest, 1x Feather Duster since they are searchable off of Sign. You can run 2 or 3 Egotist. I am running 2 in this build so we can keep the deck at 40, and it is searchable through Sign and Perfumer. If I cut Drillbeam down to 1 Egotist will go back to 3.

Channeller and Perfumer are your main normal summons. If they get negated hopefully you drew an extender. If you can bait out the interaction before resolving your Channeler and Perfumer effects that will give you the best chance to succeed. Ether Beryl is your other normal summon, and it gets you nto your Primite engine.

3x Lordly Lode, 2x Ether Beryl, and 2x Drillbeam is what I am currently using for my light primite engine. Drillbeam might go to 1. 3 Ether Beryl has felt like too much since the harpies need the normal summon as well, so 2 or 1 is probably correct. 

3x Forbidden Droplet as interaction, battle damage, and as an outlet to dump Hysteric Sign since this deck hemorrhages resources. I consider 3x to be mandatory, does a lot for the deck besides just a strong negation. You want to see this card.

3x Imperm because it has been the most consistently useful handtrap for me. Really strong. Side it out for more relevant handtraps depending on matchup.

1x Talent and 1x Called By, 1-of power cards.

1x Double Or Nothing! Absolute brick, card sucks. You do not want to draw this, you only want to search it off of Utopia Double. Allows you to swing for 10,000 with the Utopia Double setup.

Extra Deck is flexible. I am also using the Utopia Double package again. I am not a huge fan of the Utopia Double package because it adds a brick, but with Feather Storm gone we need a way to win, and I have had some success with this package in this build of the deck. Very glass cannon and quite frankly it sucks, but it does give you a way to win a game with minimal resources and you would be surprised how often this steals games. The Accesscode Talker setup is pretty nice to have, and the Spiders allow for maximizing value of normal harpies. Harpie's Phantasmal can just about win games on it's own. 2x cyber slash because they are easy to make and are disruptive. You can also go with toolbox rank 4's like Chidori or Giant Hand.

The side deck I currently have is generic. Tune it for the meta you expect to play against. Gardala is there because it is a Wind and a kaiju. Little Knight, Chidori, and a second Hunting Ground are there when I side out the Utopia Double Package.

Some variant of a Primite Engine seems to be the most viable. Not sure on numbers yet.

you get to steal monsters from field, gy, hand, deck and extra deck.

Some advanced Illusion Slop going on here.

 

The original idea was to get a combination of these engines going, as the typical Chimera-Heca and Azamina-Heca are some well known synergies. The result works out pretty well, as there are some pretty interesting lines and tech choices possible in the deck. This is also one of the reasons I included some niche cards in the deck to test them out.

Effect Veiler can be used as a way to hard fuse the Lv6 Azamina monsters with any of the Illusion monsters.

And as there are a decent amount of lines that need to send cards to the GY (with Hidden Hecehands or Diabellstar), Black Goat can be used for this turn 1 to block hand traps that activate on field (Izuna, Hollie Sue, etc.) or just as overall disruption on turn 2.

"Spell Card: Monster Reborn" is a fun card that can work well in different ways in the deck. General GY disruption, to get material for Hecahands Jauzah or Zombie Vampire on your field or to get use as fodder for starters/extenders that need to send to the GY.

 

Feel free to give some feedback on it. I think especially the extra deck could be optimized some more and I'm still experimenting with some different cards. ED space is pretty tight on the deck though, which makes it a bit more difficult. As it's a 60 card deck, you can run into problems regarding consistency, especially if you need to draw specific hand traps for enemy decks. But that's the usual problem when playing with decks that have 50+ cards.

The deck will become decently better with the new Hecahands support in Blazing Dominion though, as the new Hecahands will give the Hecahands Engine some more depth and flexibility.

deck_excerpt: Fallen of White Boy do be synchro now
deck_description:
An example decklist for Post-Burst Protocol Branded, with some spicier tech options. 

~Strengths~

Branded, as a deck, never stops running. A skilled player can navigate multiple handtraps and still build a mostly-full board, and with the new support, it's even more likely than ever. Konami also decided to print multiple absolutely insane cards for the deck, such as Branded Fusion, Branded Lost, Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon , and the new Fallen of the White Dragon, all of which make interacting with this deck a nightmare.
Branded Fusion being allowed to fusion summonusing materials from deck is an insane ability, especially with how strong the fusion toolbox is. The restriction that the monster has to use Fallen of Albaz as material does not matter when Lubellion the Searing Dragon and Albion the Branded Dragon both allow you to fusion summon a level 8 fusion without that fusion needing Albaz. The other lock it places (Fusion Monsters only for the entire turn it's activated) was a non-issue previously, however, now it is a small spot of annoyance.
Branded Lost is another particularly annoying card, as it prevents the activation of your effects that fusion summon from being negated, and prevents your opponent from responding when a monster is fusion summoned. One thing of note is that cards that negate effect are still able to stop fusion summon effects, so you can still have your Branded Fusion get hit by Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring. Adding on the effect to search an Albaz or one of his friends (Notably, Tri-Brigade Mercourier, which is a monster effect negating handtrap if you control an Albaz fusion) when you fusion summon a monster makes this one of the stronger cards in the deck.
Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon is an incredible boss monster, while a once-every-other-turn banish seems kind of bad, the fact that it extra-foolishes AND is non-targeting makes it insanely good. Plus, it's a soft-once-per-turn, so if you can manage to remake a Mirrorjade, you can use that effect again. The arguably more important part of Mirrorjade is the field nuke when the card is removed. In order for your opponent to properly avoid it, they specifically have to either negate the effect when it's activated in GY (it activates upon being sent to GY and resolves in End Phase) or they need to bounce Mirrorjade to ED/banish it facedown. 
Fallen of the White Dragon will be discussed further below.

 

Burst Protocol brings with it some really nice pieces of Branded support- notably, Fallen of the White Dragon, Ecclesia and the Dark Dragon, and Tri-Brigade Springans Kitt. 
Fallen of the White Dragon is a new 1 card starter that no doesn't require your normal summon, and allows you to set up many end phase plays by extra-foolishing either Albion the Branded Dragon or Titaniklad the Ash Dragon as cost. 
Ecclesia and the Dark Dragon is almost always what you make with Fallen of the White Dragon and Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous, as it allows you to summon either Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous or Guiding Quem, the Virtuous from your deck, which is incredibly strong. 
Tri-Brigade Springans Kitt is a nice little piece of extra help, allowing you to an Albaz, or more commonly for this deck, a monster that mentions it upon being sent to GY, allowing you to cycle back your tuners for more synchro plays, if you wish, or setting Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous up for a fusion summon. 

While previous builds played more heavily around Branded Fusion, Post-BPRO decks no longer need it to resolve in order to play the game. Summoning any synchro pervents you from taking advantage of BraFu, and activating BraFu locks you out of fusions, so the deck is a bit wacky with sequencing. If you open Fallen of the White Dragon AND Branded Fusion, you most likely use White Dragon's effect. 

Typically, a White Dragon line looks like this:

Activate Fallen of the White Dragon effect in hand to dump either Titaniklad the Ash Dragon or Albion the Branded Dragon to grave in order to summon himself.
Activate White Dragon's on-summon effect to summon an Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous from deck.
Synchro 8 for Ecclesia and the Dark Dragon.
Dark Dragon effect, banishing itself until EP to summon either Guiding Quem, the Virtuous or Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous. This is hand dependant. 
From here the turn branches off into a million different directs, as going with Cartesia allows you to start setting up an Ido the Supreme Magical Force lock via Granguignol the Dusk Dragon dumping it from deck to GY, summoning it back it Albion the Sanctifire Dragon, and while you can do this with Quem, it also requires a card leaving the extra deck to do more.
Notable locks to navigate:
Branded Opening locks you into fusions for the rest of the turn after activating.
Fusion Deployment locks you into fusions for the rest of the turn after activating.
Fallen of the White Dragon locks you into Level 8 fusions and synchros for the rest of the turn after activating the effect to summon itself.
Branded Fusion locks you into fusions the entire turn you activate it, including before activation, meaning you cannot activate it if you have synchro summoned that turn. (Notably it doesn't lock you when you copy it's ability with Fusion Duplication)

There are multiple VERY long video guides on this deck on Youtube- April's A Brief Study of Branded and MetaGamesGX's How To Play Branded in 2026: The Complete Guide (40 Hours). These guide go over a frankly unreasonable amount of combos, and while MetaGamesGX's video is the most recent, both offer a lot- April's has a free spreadsheet of combos and various hands you can get, whereas MetaGamesGX is charging for a modern spreadsheet. 

 

Notable Techs:

Etude of the Branded is another target to set with The Bystial Lubellion if you dont want to go with Branded Lost for whatever reason, and it allows you to synchro summon during either player's turn, which lets you get around being locked into Level 8s. This allows access to a suite of good level 10 synchro options- notable Bystial Dis Pater and Chaos Angel, both of which offer quite good interruptions. In order to access the Level 10 Synchros, however, you do need to use a Bystial monster (other than Bystial Lubellion). Bystial Saronir and Bystial Druiswurm are both incredible options for this, as Druiswurm provides removal and Saronir allows you get get more Branded spells in GY- setting up recursion through Branded Retribution, or protection through Branded Opening.lly

PSY-Framelord Omega lets you rip a card from your opponent's hand, denying them resources. You activate it during their Standby phase, and then, if you have Etude of the Branded up as well as 10 levels worth of syncrho material, you can summon Bystial Dis Pater in order to summon back the Framelord and deny them another card. The first card ripped will not return to hand if the same copy of Omega is summoned from banish (or otherwise leaves Banishment).

Enigmaster Packbit is great when going 2nd (or if your opponent is playing K9 and summons K9-17 Izuna), as you can effectively fully remove access to an important monster by placing it in the S/T zone (Which was the same strategy used by Snake-Eyes players to both break boards and protect their own I:P Masquerena).

SWORDSOUL IS BACK BABY!

The new branded support helps us tremendously.

1 "Fallen of the White Dragon" or 1 "Branded in High Spirits" (with a discard) makes 2 Synchros + Granguignol (or 3 Synchros instead), The Fallen & The Virtuous quickspell (which provides us with Rindbrumm in grave afterwards) and at least 2 follow ups for next turn.

1 of these Synchros is always "Ecclesia of the Black Dragon" which can be different interruption, but used mostly for special the OG Albaz from Deck and provide double interruption, thanks to mirrorjade.

If we have Suruya in hand we also end on "Swordsoul Blackout".

If you have instead a normal summon, like Mo Ye or Taia already in hand, the endboard gets an additional lvl8 Synchro.

 

The Deck is without a doubt super consistent!

 

I cutted some bricks to maximize consistency but lowered the ceiling.

 

Some tech choices worth mentioning:

You can easily make "Tenyi Spirit - Mula Adhara" which searches any fieldspell. Since we always end on 1 or 2 Spellcaster, we can abuse "Secret Village of the Spellcasters".

 

"The Iris of Swordsoul" would be easily searchable with "Swordsoul Emergence" or with the new lvl8 synchro "The Three Brave Swordsouls".

"Guardian Chimera" could easily be summoned with Cartesia if you are not locked for the turn yet.

 

For now, I'm not sure which of the lvl10 synchros I'll keep in the Main Deck. 

 

If you have anything to share or discuss, please let me know. Its my most favorite deck since its release, so I would be insanely grateful if we could make it better than rouge.
