deck_name: Structure Starter: Albaz Strike + The Fallen & The Virtuous [Domain Format]
deck_description:
The tale of Albaz does not end. It transforms.
This is a Beginner-Friendly Fusion-Focused Domain Deck made with only cards from the Albaz Strike Structure Deck and The Fallen & The Virtuous Structure Deck. 

Deckmaster: Starliege Seyfert 
Domain Restrictions: LIGHT // DARK // DRAGON 
Made for Domain Format: Join the Community Discord!

To create this decklist, please add these 21 cards from the Albaz Strike Structure Deck to The Fallen & The Virtuous Structure Deck: 
Note: Dogmatika Fleurdelis, Dogmatika Ecclesia, Fusion Deployment and Triple Tactics Trust from the Structure Deck will be Alternate Arts

  • ydke://EtFCBR0t6AKWoVQDaIi1AX6w6gThibADoXYGAFL3igOyMswFbuiIAGbx/wF2W1wBJpBCAzxDbgQ+pHEBy0uSAxImlAUWX9cEhd//A7NnrgA=!!rbPqAA==!
  • View on YGOprodeck
  • Albaz Strike Structure Deck Full Contents (YGOprodeck)
  • The Fallen & The Virtuous Structure Deck Full Contents (Yugipedia)

Additional Resources can be found here:
https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1c8_W7TLHoExz9Iq2yNBKG4kniKN3fjamfMVRehPRitQ/edit?usp=sharing

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.

Refer here for additional rules and exceptions:

https://www.domainformat.com/rules 

Broad Categories

This simple strategy has cards that fall into three simple categories:

  • The Fusion Effects
  • The End Phase
  • The Spellcasters

Primary Packages: Branded, Dogmatika

Recommended Branded Guides (from paktcg, MetaGamesGX, April):

  • https://youtube.com/watch?v=U9oJwRlVeNQ
  • https://youtube.com/watch?v=xGgvjm6CV_U 
  • https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zzGGAi7Yyrg 

Alternate Decklist:

  • Structure Starter: The Fallen & The Virtuous

Fusion Effects
- Branded Fusion is your bread and butter
- Summoning Fallen of Albaz is an alternate route to Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon 
- Branded in Red and Branded in White are your backup

The Branded deck's most powerful endboard piece is Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon. This card offers a non-targetting banish effect (for monsters), a rare and flexible disruption/removal option. Additionally, Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon also sends a card from our Extra Deck to the GY which allows us to generate even more advantage in the End Phase. 

The easiest way to obtain a Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon is through the effect of Branded Fusion. This card allows you to fuse without using any monsters from hand or field, allowing the creation of a Fusion monster from just one card. Your typical targets for Branded Fusion are Lubellion the Searing Dragon or Albion the Branded Dragon, both of which can immediatly activate their effects in order to fusion one more time and create a Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon. 

This deck has various ways to search the powerful Branded Fusion including:

  • Aluber the Jester of Despia (searchable with Branded Opening, Despian Tragedy)
  • Springans Kitt (searchable with Branded in High Spirits, Tri-Brigade Mercourier)
  • Keeper of Dragon Magic
  • Summoner Monk 
  • Triple Tactics Thrust 

Typically with Branded Fusion you will send The Bystial Lubellion alongside Fallen of Albaz to create Albion the Branded Dragon before then fusing Fallen of Albaz in GY with another DARK from hand/field to make Lubellion the Searing Dragon before creating Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon (with Lubellion the Searing Dragon + Fallen of Albaz in Banishment). This allows you to use The Bystial Lubellion in GY tributing Albion the Branded Dragon to summon itself and search the powerful Branded Lost. This allows allow you to activate the GY effect of Albion the Branded Dragon in GY to set a powerful Branded Spell/Trap. 

With the power of Branded Fusion being so impactful, it is likely that your opponents will focus on negating or otherwise stopping the effect of it. Fortunately, Branded Fusion is not our only path to Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon thanks to the powerful effect of Fallen of Albaz. Upon summon, we are able to Fusion Summon using Fallen of Albaz and one of our opponent's monsters! This means that if your opponent has any LIGHT/DARK, we would be able to make Lubellion the Searing Dragon or Albion the Branded Dragon to make Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon anyways. Or if they have any Syncro/XYZ/Link/Fusion monster, we can just directly make Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon with it and Fallen of Albaz! 

Ways to summon Fallen of Albaz from Deck:

  • Fusion Deployment
  • Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous
  • Guiding Quem, the Virtuous 
  • Summoner Monk 

Suppose that Fallen of Albaz is also stopped. Now we move to backup plans! If you have Fallen of Albaz in GY or Field, all you need now is a Light or Dark monster to make Albion the Branded Dragon or Lubellion the Searing Dragon in order to get to Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon anyways. Therefore, you will want to recover the Albaz from GY/Banishment (if not on field/hand) and activate a Fusion effect to get going. 

Recover Albaz Effects: 

  • Branded in Red 
  • Branded in White 
  • Guiding Quem, the Virtuous 
  • Branded Bond
  • Rindbrumm the Striking Dragon 

Fusion Effects: 

  • Branded in Red  
  • Branded in White  
  • Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous
  • Super Polymerization 
  • Fusion Gate  
  • Fusion Substitute  
  • Fusion Recycling Plant 
  • Necro Fusion 
  • Branded Banishment  
  • Fusion Duplication 

Note that Branded in Red and Branded in White are in both lists. These are immensly powerful cards that both Fusion Summon and provide material for the Fusion Summon, making resolving them very similar to resolving a Branded Fusion. Notably, Branded in Red can be searched and activated in the End Phase if you have Albion the Branded Dragon in the GY.  

End Phase
- Main Phase 3, even on your opponent's turn! 
- Trigger all the effects of the Albaz Fusions
- Engine Access (Albaz Fusion GY effects -> Guiding Quem, the Virtuous // Branded in Red) 
- Resource Regeneration (Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous // Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous // Branded in High Spirits)

Throughout the turn, Branded will put Fusions into the GY through Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon, Granguignol the Dusk Dragon and through various effects like Branded in High Spirits, The Fallen & The Virtuous and Nadir Servant. These fusion's GY effects will trigger in the End Phase, giving us oppertunities to obtain Endboard Pieces and Polymerization effects.

Albaz Dragons and typical searched cards from their GY effect: 

  • Albion the Branded Dragon - Branded in Red , The Fallen & The Virtuous , Branded Banishment , Branded Retribution , Branded Fusion , Branded Opening 
  • The Dragon that Devours the Dogma - Tri-Brigade Mercourier , The Fallen & The Virtuous , Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous , Guiding Quem, the Virtuous 
  • Brigrand the Glory Dragon - Tri-Brigade Mercourier
  • Titaniklad the Ash Dragon - Guiding Quem, the Virtuous , Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous   
  • Sprind the Irondash Dragon - Springans Kitt
  • Alba-Lenatus the Abyss Dragon - Fusion Deployment, Fusion Substitute, Branded Fusion     

Diving into this deeper, you will find that Albion the Branded Dragon has the most searchable cards. During the end phase, you may choose endboard pieces in Branded Retribution // Branded Banishment // Branded Opening or a polymerization effect in Branded in Red. The Branded in Red can be used immediatly during that same End Phase. This is most effective when you are able to return Fallen of Albaz from GY and fuse into Lubellion the Searing Dragon with a Dark Monster.

Another way to obtain Branded in Red during the End Phase is through Springans Kitt summoned through the GY effect of Sprind the Irondash Dragon. You may also decide to use Springans Kitt recycle a Branded Trap from your GY/Banished to Deck before resolving the Albion the Branded Dragon in order to immediatly set a Branded card from Deck.

During the End Phase, various Main Deck cards will have have effects to set themselves from GY or return from GY to hand.
The cards that set themselves from GY if they were sent there to activate the effect of Fallen of Albaz are: Screams of the Branded , Judgment of the Branded , Branded Bond , Branded in White. These cards are most notable when sent to GY due to the GY effect of Albion the Shrouded Dragon who is treated as "Fallen of Albaz" while in the GY.
The cards that return from GY to hand are: Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous, Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous , and Branded in High Spirits. These cards increase the resource loop of the deck, allowing you fodder to discard for cards like Fallen of Albaz , Branded Opening , and Lubellion the Searing Dragon. 

In the worst case scenerio: Try to activate as many effects as possible that send Fusions from Extra Deck to GY, whether that be through card effects or fusing/tributing your Fusion monsters on the field.

The Spellcasters
- Access Recycling
- Another way to make or revive Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon 

The Spellcasters Guiding Quem, the Virtuous and Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous are fablous endboard pieces to use in the cases where we are unable to resolve our other effects. Both have effects that can be used in your opponents turn to access fusions. Let's discuss them one by one.

Guiding Quem, the Virtuous has an effect to send a card that mentions Fallen of Albaz to GY. These cards typically have GY effects.
Utility cards to send through Guiding Quem, the Virtuous:

  • Branded Sword 
  • Branded Retribution 
  • Branded Opening 

Most Notable is Branded Retribution, with the GY effect to add a Branded Spell/Trap from GY to hand. If you are able to send/have powerful Branded Spells in GY like Branded in Red or Branded Fusion, you can use Branded Retribution to add it back to hand in order to activate or set them. A way to send Branded Spells to GY is Bystial Saronir 

The more notable effect of Guiding Quem, the Virtuous is to revive a card that mentions Fallen of Albaz.
If you do not yet have Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon, you can use Guiding Quem, the Virtuous to revive Fallen of Albaz to attempt to fuse with your opponent's monsters or revive Springans Kitt // Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous in order to use a Fusion Effect.  
If you do have a powerful Albaz Fusion in GY, you can simply revive that Fusion monster! Notably, Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon effect can be activated once-per-copy, so if you can use Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon effect twice a single turn if you use Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon , send it to GY (typically through fusing with it through Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous), and revive it again! You may also decide to destroy your own Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon through battle or The Fallen & The Virtuous knowing that you can revive it through Guiding Quem, the Virtuous, allowing you to use Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon twice a turn. 
If you have an Albaz Fusion on field, you may choose to revive a Tri-Brigade Mercourier in order to access a negate.

However, to activate Guiding Quem, the Virtuous's powerful revival effect, you will need to see a card leave the Extra Deck. This can happen if any player summons from the Extra Deck, or if we use an effect that sends a card from our Extra Deck to GY (Branded in High Spirits, The Fallen & The Virtuous, Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon, Dogmatika Maximus and Nadir Servant)

You will typically summon Guiding Quem, the Virtuous through Titaniklad the Ash Dragon (GY effect), Granguignol the Dusk Dragon , or Branded Opening.
Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous has an effect in hand to summon itself if Fallen of Albaz is on field/GY. Ways to send Fallen of Albaz to GY are Albion the Shrouded Dragon and Branded Fusion.  

Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous has the powerful effect to Fusion Summon as a Quick Effect. Due to being a Quick Effect that can be used on both our turn and our opponents, just a single negation will not stop Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous. If simply negated for the turn through Effect Veiler for instance, you can try again to fuse on your opponent's turn. Remember that the easiest ways to make Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon is if you are able to make Albion the Branded Dragon or Lubellion the Searing Dragon.

Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous also has its own signiture fusion monster called Granguignol the Dusk Dragon, which is easy to create due to only needing Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous and any Light/Dark monster. This is a deceptively good endboard due to being able to send a LIGHT/DARK monster from deck or Extra Deck to GY.  

Granguignol the Dusk Dragon typical targets:

  • Albaz Dragons (see above) 
  • Rindbrumm the Striking Dragon 
  • Albion the Shrouded Dragon 
  • Bystial Saronir 

By sending an Albaz Dragon, we would be able to access Guiding Quem, the Virtuous or powerful fusion effect like Branded in Red during the end phase. Granguignol the Dusk Dragon would also be able to banish itself to summon Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous or Guiding Quem, the Virtuous if your opponent summons a monster using a monster effect. This would add a Fusion Effect through Guiding Quem, the Virtuous sending/summoning Fallen of Albaz or add a negate through Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous searching Dogmatika Fleurdelis, the Knighted.
Another option would be to send Rindbrumm the Striking Dragon , and hope that an opponent triggers Granguignol the Dusk Dragon to summon Guiding Quem, the Virtuous. This would allow Guiding Quem, the Virtuous to send Fallen of Albaz to GY, enabling the GY effect of Rindbrumm the Striking Dragon  to summon Fallen of Albaz. 

Ways to search Guiding Quem, the Virtuous: Branded in High Spirits , Tri-Brigade Mercourier , Branded Lost , Branded Opening , Nadir Servant , Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous , Titaniklad the Ash Dragon 

Ways to search Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous: Branded in High Spirits , Tri-Brigade Mercourier , Branded Lost, Fusion Deployment , Guiding Quem, the Virtuous 

Notable Interactions:

  • Guiding Quem, the Virtuous + Fallen of Albaz (GY)
  • Guiding Quem, the Virtuous + Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon (GY) or Tri-Brigade Mercourier (GY)
  • Albion the Branded Dragon -> Search Branded in Red (Fallen of Albaz in GY)
  • Sprind the Irondash Dragon -> Summon Springans Kitt -> Search Branded in Red (Fallen of Albaz in GY)
  • Rindbrumm the Striking Dragon + Fallen of Albaz (GY)
  • Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous + Fallen of Albaz 
  • Branded in High Spirits + Dragon monster -> Search Springans Kitt 
  • Branded Retribution + Branded Spell/Trap in GY
  • Albion the Branded Dragon or Branded in Red -> Banish Despian Tragedy -> Search Aluber the Jester of Despia or Guiding Quem, the Virtuous 
  • Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous -> Search Dogmatika Fleurdelis, the Knighted or Dogmatika Maximus or The Fallen & The Virtuous or Dogmatika Punishment 
  • Foolish Burial -> Send Despian Tragedy -> Search Aluber the Jester of Despia or Guiding Quem, the Virtuous 
  • Gold Sarcophagus -> Banish Despian Tragedy -> Search Aluber the Jester of Despia or Guiding Quem, the Virtuous 
  • Gold Sarcophagus -> Banish Tri-Brigade Mercourier -> Search Springans Kitt or Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous or Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous

Gameplans

Endboard Pieces: Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon , Tri-Brigade Mercourier , Rindbrumm the Striking Dragon , The Dragon that Devours the Dogma , Branded Retribution , The Fallen & The Virtuous 
Extend/Recover: Springans Kitt , Branded in Red , Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous , Branded in High Spirits , Branded in White 
Backup Plan: Granguignol the Dusk Dragon , Guiding Quem, the Virtuous , Nadir Servant
Searchable Utility:  Chaos Dragon Levianeer , Bystial Druiswurm , Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon , Fallen of Albaz 
Grindgame: Lubellion the Searing Dragon , Springans Kitt , Despian Tragedy , Branded Retribution , Branded Sword

Recap: 

Important Cards: Branded Fusion , Fallen of Albaz , Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous , Guiding Quem, the Virtuous 
Strategy Elevator Pitch: Resource loops disguised as combos.

This deck consistently reaches Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon through redundant Fusion lines rather than relying on a single card, using Fallen of Albaz, backup Fusion effects, and Quick-Effect Spellcasters to play through disruption. Its primary strength is the End Phase, where Albaz Fusion monsters in the GY translate into searches, sets, and recovery that sustain interaction every turn, prioritizing recursion, flexibility, and long-term advantage over explosive one-turn boards.

Recommened Upgrades: Fallen of the White Dragon , Ecclesia and the Dark Dragon , The Iris Swordsoul 

Stop the Fusion? Fine. Try stopping the End Phase.

This deck has come a long way from where it started well over a decade ago. What once was just two of the Six Samurai structure decks and a few extra cards is now an incredibly potent and I believe tournament level deck. After a few of the first edits to actually make this semi-workable I actually made the mistake that led to this deck's name; I added Obelisk the Tormentor thinking the summoning power of the Six Samurai would make good tribute fodder for the Egyptian God Card. I was right about that, but I was wrong in thinking that Obelisk would really be a boon to this archetype. 

The other great change made not too long ago was the addition of Secret Six Samurai Fuma to replace Shien's Squire as a Level 1 Tuner but also the addition of Secret Six Samura Hatsume. 

The most recent changes are the addition of The Legendary Lord Six Samurai monsters and the Tactical Trainer and Anarchist Monk tuner monsters.

deck_description:
The ratios are a bit wonky, but it is serviceable; I found that since Selande also searches the fusion spell, and Daneen can fusion summon, playing 2 Kimridge is ok since the spell is not something you need to resolve first thing during your turn. I think 2 Noma is good as well, since you can sometimes banish her using Haggard Lizardose to get a draw, or tribute her in a pinch for the mitsu stuff or ultra evolution pill.

The main objective is to get your deck as thinned out of non-GMX and Dinosaur cards as possible before you activate Applied experiment #55, and preferably stack some materials on top using Noma and/or Kimridge. The mills off of Zombie Vampire are helpful in this as well. So are the draws you can get from Dugares, Haggard Lizardose and potentially others. 

Chicken game obviously CANNOT prevent the loss of lifepoints, only damage. It is mainly there to thin out your deck even further - you can access it easily with Horned saurus, which you can also fuse into using Daneen if you don't get Kaito on the field from the hand. The deck is honestly pretty decent at getting material on board. Mitsu does what it always does, as do the generic dinos. The side deck is pretty much just there for the sake of it, better options surely exist. 

All in all, I think this is interesting, maybe a better deckbuilder than me can even make it somewhat viable. This was my first thought when I started to think of an archetype to combine with GMX, and while I was building this deck (I started before they had even revealed the final cards of 1st wave, lol), I saw others, much better players (like Joshua Schmidt) had also seen that there might be something, maybe not great, but playable here, so shout out to them!

Just a little something I've been tinkering with. It can put up surprisingly decent endboards. I went a bit over 40 just to try to lower the times you draw bricks (although, if you wanna play more Charmers to avoid that, that's something you could do).

 

Konami please give us another wave of Charmer support to smooth out the edges of the deck. It's one step away from being decent!!!

deck_name: Ultimate Engine of Destruction (Blue-Eyes, Buster Blader, Primite, Metalmorph)
deck_excerpt: Dragon of White, Dragon of Black, and the Dragon Destroyer...can you stand before their incredible destructive force?
deck_description:
The Blue-Eyes White Dragon...does it really need an introduction? The answer is no, but here's one anyway. The ace-monster of Seto Kaiba from the Duel Monsters era of the anime has received a frankly insane amount of support over the years, allowing its associated deck to be meta-viable several times throughout its lifespan, and although it has currently fallen off the current meta, I believe it has the potential to make a 2nd/3rd/4th comeback even with the explosive power of today's strongest decks lined up against it. Would this build be the key to its victory? I'll let you decide.

Now, I know you're looking at a 50 card Main Deck and thinking that this brew doesn't have a chance, but hear me out and let me explain my madness before you judge it too harshly. I promise there's a method to it all. Let's start with a quick breakdown of the supplementary engines involved in this build, those being Primite, Buster Blader, Metalmorph/Bystial, and Crimson Dragon.

  1. Primite: Unsurprisingly, an engine that was designed to support Normal Monsters is a no-brainer for a deck that revolves around the strongest Normal Monster in the game, and yet, the synergy between the two decks is so complete that you'd almost think that Konami designed one with the other in mind.
    1. Ether Beryl and Lordly Lode serve functionally the same purpose in the Deck, one searching the other which then searches the other cards in the engine. That said, it's arguable to say that seeing Ether Beryl in your opening hand is slightly better, given that if the search effect of either is negated or your opponent hits you with a Droll & Lock Bird you can still use Ether Beryl to Link Summon into the Spirit with Eyes of Blue and continue on with your combo.
    2. Drillbeam is undoubtedly the best search target once the engine's been established, allowing you to negate and banish any card on the field so long as you have a Normal Monster or a Primite monster in your hand/on the field...and given how easy this is to accomplish if you have True Light on the field, which in and of itself is exceedingly easy for the Deck just by going through normal combos, it's almost a guarantee that Drillbeam will be live once it's in your grip.
    3. Although not quite as strong as Drillbeam, Roar is nonetheless a good option to search off Ether Beryl/Lordly Lode, allowing you to summon a Blue-Eyes White Dragon in situations where you need the extra body as well as disrupting your opponent with its GY effect.
  2. Buster Blader: Unlike Primite, Buster Blader doesn't seem to have been custom-made to work alongside Blue-Eyes, and yet, there are enough incidental synergies between the two archetypes that they do work well together.
    1. Because Buster Whelp is a Level 1 Light Tuner Dragon monster, it can be searched with the Normal Summon efffect of Sage, it can be extra Normal Summoned by the effect of Mausoleum, and it can be used as material to summon Spirit with Eyes of Blue, Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon and Hieratic Seal of Heavenly Spheres, the latter two of which you ideally want on your final end board.
    2. Speaking of the end board, the engine's main power duo, Buster Dragon and the Dragon Destroyer Swordsman, lock your opponent out of activating their monster effects on field and prevent all but Link Monsters from attacking, and can both easily be summoned off a single activation of Prologue, give or take a few steps.
      1. It should also be noted that, because you technically only require Prologue to get these two monsters out since neither Destruction Sword Memories or Dragon Destroyer Swordsman require Destruction Sword monsters as material, seeing Prologue in your opening hand is hardly an issue, as Blue-Eyes is more than capable of filling the GY with Dragons to use as Fusion material for DSM.
  3. Metalmorph/Bystial: Unlike Primite and Buster Blader, the Metalmorph engine admittedly doesn't have as many synergies with Blue-Eyes; that said, there are enough to make it viable in the Deck, especially when it's coupled with the small Bystial package included in the list.
    1. Because Fullmetal Dragon requires a tribute of a Level 5 or higher Dragon, Blue-Eyes is able to fulfill this requirement, as are the Bystials, and adding it to the end board gives you an omni-negate that can't be targeted or destroyed by Monster or Spell effects.
      1. It should also be noted that, because Fullmetal Dragon sets Max Metalmorph directly from the Deck, it plays around both Ash Blossom and Droll & Lock Bird, which is a nice bonus.
    2. Because the Bystials require Lights/Darks in the GY to banish, Blue-Eyes is also able to fulfill this requirement easily, as is Buster Blader by-the-by, if your opponent isn't playing a Light/Dark focused strategy, and becasue they are Dragons, they can also be used as material to summon Hieratic Seals.
  4. Crimson Dragon: Because of the ease of which Blue-Eyes can get Level 1 Tuners and Level 8 Dragons on the field, it is exceedingly easy to get two Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragons on the field, meaning that it's also exceedingly easy to set up Crimson Dragon and the associated powerhouses it entails.
    1. The main target for Crimson Dragon is Sifr Divine Dragon, using Ultimate Spirit Dragon as its target. Getting these two Dragons out represents an omni-negate and a Monster negate, and because Sifr Divine Dragon protects your cards from destruction once each, it prevents Ultimate Spirit from being destroyed by regular Spirit Dragon's effect during the End Phase and can protect your True Light from being destroyed on your opponent's turn, thus preventing a potential board wipe.
    2. As a secondardy target, we have Abyss Dragon, which can use either Spirit Dragon or Lightstorm Dragon as its targets, and also represents and omni-negate on board.
      1. As a side-note, you can also just naturally summon Abyss Dragon if you have Buster Dragon on field alongside one of the Deck's many Level 1 Tuners, which is a nice additional bonus for its inclusion.

With all of that out of the way, let's take a moment to talk about the Deck's game plan.

  1. As is, the Deck as three viable Normal Summons, those being Sage, Buster Whelp, and Ether Beryl.
    1. Because all three of these can be linked off for Spirit with Eyes of Blue, seeing any combination of two of these in your opening hand grants you access to Spirit Dragon at minimum, as well as opening up either full Buster Blader or Primite combos.
      1. As noted above, it isn't technically necessary to access the Buster Blader portion of the Deck if you have Prologue in your opening hand, meaning that in a "Best of All Worlds" situation, you would have that plus Sage and Ether Beryl in your opening hand to gain access to all three engines at the same time.
      2. It should also be noted that, of the three, Sage is the best Normal Summon, as it grants you access to all of the Deck's other Tuners, all of which have powerful effects in their own right.
  2. Alongside these, the Deck has three primary extenders that you either want in your opening hand or will need to search through your normal combos, those being Maiden, Wishes, and Kaibaman.
    1. Without a doubt, Maiden is the card you want to get access to as quickly as possible, making it the premiere target for Sage's search effect if you don't find it in your opening hand. Being able to place True Light on your field is paramount to the Deck's strategy, both as a way to search the Deck's powerfull Spell/Traps and to get a Blue-Eyes on field, while its Special Summon effects grant you access to both Syncrho and Link plays.
    2. Much like Maiden, Wishes is a card you want to see as soon as possible, either in your opening hand or by searching it with True Light, as it is another card that grants you access to all of the Deck's myriad Tuners, while its GY effect will give your Blue-Eyes monsters targeting protection via Neo Ultimate Dragon.
    3. Admittedly, Kaibaman isn't as crucial to the Deck as the other two extenders, hence why there's only a single copy in the list. That said, in hands where you already have access to Maiden, Kaibaman is a phenomenal search target off of Sage, as it can easily set up the Crimson Dragon line by getting an addition Blue-Eyes on the field and its GY effect can give you easy access to Jet Dragon if you don't already have it.
      1. The one downside of Kaibaman is that, being a Warrior instead of a Spellcaster, it cannot be used to Summon Spirit with Eyes of Blue; however, in scenarios where you have access to any of the Deck's other Tuners, this is hardly an issue, as you can simply use Kaibaman and the Blue-Eyes it summons to make Spirit Dragon and use your other Tuners for the rest of the combo.
  3. Unfortunately, because your endboard is dependent on which parts of the Deck you see in your opening hand, it's difficult to definitively say what it should look like. At minimum...and if you don't get interupted...you should have a Spirit Dragon and a Hieratic Seal on field, alongside whatever engine parts you opened/searched throughout the combo. That said, the ceiling for this Deck is considerably higher, and with the right combination of cards in hand, you can end on a board that will leave your opponent with scant options if you go uninterupted. That combination: Sage, Prologue, Fullmetal Dragon, and Ether Beryl/Lordly Lode. Here's how the combo goes:
    1. Normal Summon Ether Beryl/activate Lordly Lode; search whichever one you didn't open.
    2. Activate Lordly Lode/Normal Summon Ether Beryl; search Drillbeam.
    3. Link off Ether Beryl for Spirit with Eyes of Blue; search Mausoleum.
    4. Activate Mausoleum; activate effect to extra Normal Summon Sage; search Maiden.
    5. Discard Maiden to place True Light.
    6. Activate Mausoleum effect, target Sage/Spirit and send Blue-Eyes to the GY.
    7. Tribute Spirit to Summon Blue-Eyes from the GY; Special Summon Maiden from the GY.
    8. Activate True Light, placing Wishes from Deck.
    9. Activate Wishes, discarding the 5th card in your hand; add Roar and add either Effect Veiler for insulation or Sage/Kaibaman for follow-up.
    10. Banish Wishes from the GY, equipping Blue-Eyes with Neo Ultimate Dragon.
    11. Activate Roar, summoning Jet from Deck.
    12. Synchro Summon two Spirit Dragons, using all four monsters on field; tribute both Spirit Dragons, summoning Ultimate Spirit and Crimson Dragon; search Synchro Rumble with Crimson Dragon.
    13. Activate Crimson Dragon, targeting Ultimate Spirit, and Summon Sifr Dragon.
    14. Reveal Fullmetal Dragon to set Max Metalmoprh.
    15. Set both Prologue and Drillbeam and pass turn; during the End Phase, Sifr Dragon protects Ultimate Spirit from being destroyed.
    16. During your opponent's Draw Phase, activate both Prologue to Summon Buster Dragon by sending Buster Blader and Destruction Sword Memories and True Light to Summon Blue-Eyes from the GY; before leaving the Draw Phase, activate Destruction Sword Memories, banishing it, Buster Blader, and Spirit with Eyes of Blue to Summon Dragon Destroyer Swordsman.
      1. With all this on board, you have two omni-negates, one from Ultimate Spirit and one from Drillbeam; you have a monster negate from Sifr Dragon that stops any in hand effects, as well as built in protection for your True Light; you're negating all your opponent's on-field monster effects with Buster Blader/Buster Dragon, as well as putting everything they summon that isn't a Link monster to Defense; you have targeting protection for your Blue-Eyes, both from True Light and Neo Ultimate Dragon, and targeting protection for your Ultimate Spirit with Neo Ultimate Dragon; and if/when you've used Drillbeam, you can then use the Blue-Eyes on field to activate Max Metalmorph and Summon Fullmetal Dragon for another omni-negate.

With all that said, the Deck isn't without its weaknessess.

  1. Droll & Lock Bird: Although both Maiden and Fullmetal Dragon are able to play around this card, the Deck still wants to do a lot of searching between Sage, Buster Whelp, Ether Beryl/Lordly Lode, and Wishes, meaning seeing this card from your opponent will likely hamstring your combos; the recent semi-limit of the card might help with this issue slightly, and it's too early in the format to know if Droll will still be widespread, though chances are high that it likely will be.
  2. The Mulcharmies (mostly Fuwalos): Because the Deck wants to Special Summon a lot, seeing a Mulcharmy dropped on you can be devastating, Fuwalos in particular though Meowls can be annoying too...Purulia isn't much of a hassle, since the Deck doesn't really Summon from hand besides the Bystials.
  3. As stated above, the potential output of the Deck is almost entirely dependent on what halves of the Deck you see in your opening hand; likewise, although it's less likely to happen now after the introduction of Maiden, Wishes, and Spirit with Eyes of Blue, it is still possible for the Deck to live up to the "Brick-Eyes" moniker that plagued it for so many years before the latest structure deck, as there are a number of cards you almost never want to see in your opening hand outside of a very few, niche situations (i.e. Buster Blader, Destruction Sword Memories, Ultimate Fusion, Syncrho Rumble).

All in all, the Deck is a lot of fun to play, and as I stated above, I think it could potentially still compete with the current meta if given the chance.

deck_description: Long combo deck that can Solphacord full combo for 1.5 negates into Yummy full combo into Mitsu full combo. 1/3 cards in this deck is a 1 card starter for at least 1 of the three archetypes allowing it to be 60 cards so that Mitsu bricks are less likely to be drawn.
Somehow made a worse version of the "(WCT-04) Generic Harpie Lady Deck", since Mai barely plays any cards that are actually in the game.

I think the only two things you could reasonably debate regarding this list are the two extra deck slots where I put Salamangreat Sunlight Wolf and Duelittle Chimera, as well as which of Infinite Impermanence and Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion should be in main.

My reasoning for including Duelittle Chimera is that, in my opinion, Fire King High Avatar Kirin is the most broken card in the deck. Having it in hand allows you to play though so much interaction, and the float + non-target pop you get when it is destroyed is one of the most important effects in the whole deck. Being able to recycle this card even once is incredibly valuble, as it fixes the deck's only flaw in the grind game (running out of good cards to pop with Sacred Fire King Garunix), and also allows you to continue playing through interaction. As for Salamangreat Sunlight Wolf, it gives you access to a combo that can convert a hand of just Legendary Fire King Ponix + any FIRE monster into your full endboard. That combo is also pretty resilient towards pre-end phase Nibiru, the Primal Being, as the Legendary Fire King Ponix will add back to your hand during your oppenents ensuing standby phase, giving you another FIRE monster to pop with Fire King High Avatar Kirin. Salamangreat Sunlight Wolf also has the ability to recycle Fire King High Avatar Kirin, and although it doesn't serve that purpose as well as Duelittle Chimera, the ability to do that at all greatly improves the deck's grind game.

Infinite Impermanence vs Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion is almost entirely personal preference. I chose Infinite Impermanence because it synergizes with Dominus Impulse, and also helps to out towers and floodgates if you open with it going second. Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion is also a good option for different reasons.

Join the Domain Format discord server for information on rules and deckbuilding: https://discord.gg/jGkRCJkt3d

(Multiply Guy is a proxy for Multiplying Kuriboh) With Vidrium as our deck master, we can search Terminus, which searches any Dark Fairy from our deck. We grab Darklord Djehuty and do a standard Darklord combo that ends on a board nuke using The First Darklord, a Spell/Trap negate with Herald of Mirage Lights, and any of the Darklord traps that can also be copied by Ixchel! When we reach our second turn, we can use Vidrium to search Zegredo and scale it with Vidrium for a 1-11 Pendulum Scale, letting us Pendulum Summon a bunch of powerful monsters! Nervedo can also be used to summon Nerva, which lets us nuke another player's field. That allows Vidria to debuff our opponents' monsters so we can easily end the duel with Vidrium's massive 10000 attack and it's protection to monster effects!

Category: Tournament Meta Decks (Asian-English OCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Irfan Nur Afif

Tournament: T-OCG Premium OTS – January 24th 2026

Placement: 2nd Place

Kimridge, Selande, Miscellaneousaurus and Applied Experiment let you access Mitsuguri through Animadorned Archosaur destorying ALLOS. GMX Noma is a reptile so she can be sent for Mitsuguri Ritual and revived by Futsu to remove a card from the opponent's GY and fuse into VELOX for more interuption. If you already have access to Habakiri the GMX cards can be uses to make Photon Lord as ALLOS can revive another copy of himself.

This deck does too much to be running Revolt in the main. I'll think about maining it when i remember how to do optimal Tri-Brigade lines, for now Rugal in the extra deck is fine lmao.

 

If you need to side out the Charmer cards in main (aside from Hiita since she's a synergistic searcher), I've included Nib and Impulse in the side deck. Haven't tested how much Impulse messes with the extra deck pieces, you can swap it out for a different piece of disruption if you need to. It should be fine though (Kerass withstanding).

 

Main reason i opted to build it this way is because if i'm going to go into my Charmer fusion monster, i don't want to get Drolled mid-combo. Its the biggest issue i have with the Crowley extender (especially since the new time rules incentivize running lingering floodgates like Droll), so i'd rather just hard draw the Spellbook or open with something else that's useful if i don't see it. But if I do see it in my opening hand, i'll be guaranteed to play through Droll since you'll only have to search your deck once to set up your end board. Aside from that, i chose Fire King as my main engine because it has a lot of tools to discard charmers in your hand if you draw any of them. That way if you open a charmer and the spellbook, you'll have a means of getting your charamer into the GY so that your spell will be live.

deck_excerpt: TCG Approved deck - Primite at full power.
deck_description:
ALL CARDS IN THIS DECK HAVE BEEN RELEASED IN THE TCG - THIS IS A TCG FORMATTED DECK.
YGOPRODECK HASN'T ADDED PRIMITE FUSION INTO THE TCG FRAMEWORK, AND THIS LISTING WILL BE UPDATED ACCORDINGLY WHEN IT HAS.

This is my favorite Yu-Gi-Oh deck of all time.

What was once a casual normal monster exhibition deck used to teach people the way the game is played for each new extra deck mechanic added to the game - turned into a tightly fitted control deck that uses normal monsters and a Primite engine to its absolute maximum ability. Understanding why the sideboard has a bunch of normal monsters in it as well as the actual decklist is what it is, requires you - the player - to understand key elements of the game that are often overlooked in the modern Yu-Gi-Oh space - as well as understanding what kind of deck that the opponent is playing.

DISCLAIMER
In order to play this deck well, you have to read the types and elements of your opponent's deck, and accomidate the sideboard accordingly. This deck's power comes from utilizing the complete chromatic spectrum of elements to undermine your opponent's board state.

To put it simply, each monster that has been chosen has been researched in that it accomidates a slot of the normal monster line-up. For example, is your opponent going DARK / LIGHT? Replace the corresponding monster elements in the deck. Is it a Blue-Eyes deck? (Light-Spellcaster) / (Light Dragon) Add Watttaildragon and Flame Manipulator. Predaplant or Traptrix?  (Earth/Plant / Dark/Plant) --- Jerry Beans Man and Genex Controller. 

The deck's main core takes care of the rest and remains static - all of which is intended and functions around Lvs 3 / 6 / 9
Each monster has been carefully researched to be put in this deck for maximum synergy.
There are 9 one-card starters in this deck.
There are 9 spot removal cards. All spot removals are reusable every turn.
There are 3 Hand Traps - That same hand trap also is a board wipe - and can be searched out by the Primite support.

Draco Masters of the Tenyi is the Raigeki of the deck.
Lightstorm Dragon is your Harpie's Feather Duster.
First of the Dragons / First of the Dragonlords are your nigh-unbeatable walls that cannot be destroyed by battle by effect monsters and are unaffected by monster effects.

All Primite Support powers up the normal monsters that you run. Lordly Lode's buffs your monsters by 300 for each normal monster in the grave, and Piercing the Darkness acts as an Honest-esque battle insurance and additional card draw.
And because of the type/element diversity, you can main deck "There Can Only Be One" instead of running Primite Roar and leave both Primite Roars in the sideboard.

The new Tri-Brigade Springans Kitt and Gung-Ho! Springans! finally lets the deck actually accomplish something without requiring some janky secondary engine like Mathmech.
it also lets you cut down on a bunch of cards that I've been wanting to cut for ages like the old Springans Kitt and Branded in High Spirits.

New Kitt's revival effect triggering when send to grave from anywhere is really nice as it can be used when detaching from an xyz, as can Gung-Ho to special Springans Captain Sargas  from deck which is incorporated into the endboard by tucking it under a Number F0: Utopic Draco Future  or Number F0: Utopic Future Zexal, giving some level of layered interaction to the endboard. Additionally, due to the deck having more room to generate bodies on its own, its not far-fetched to utilise Springans Branga's graveyard effect to search Springans Interluder , an omni-negate trap
as well as ending on a springans xyz to fuel it alongside the typical endboard (still debating on cutting something for Sprind the Irondash Dragon  in the ED to fuel merrymaker in this situation).

Gung-ho Springans finally lets you add Therion "King" Regulus  to the endboard consistently as opposed to a secondary search option off Gigantic "Champion" Sargas. 
During the main combo, you use Springans Rockey and new Kitt to make Gung-ho, detach both to summon Regulus. This then triggers Kitt to special the Rockey and he then triggers to add back Kitt, who can special herself, to make another rank 4, typically either Merrymaker if you searched Interluder or Gallant Granite  to search Nibiru, the Primal Being.

The spirits are used as a small engine to facilitate a one card combo within the deck, think tour guide in unchained. An Onomat engine can also achieve this, and probably to a more powerful extent, however I have a soul and this is meant to be a more pure variant of the deck instead of just a worse version of Onomat Ryzeal. Mitsu could also work but, again, worse Ryzeal.
Aratama  lets you add Ichiki Sayori-Hime  (who incidentally works with Rockey) who normals itself to search another Aratama for follow up, and then makes Merrymaker to full combo.
Sakitama  is the ultimate extender, making any level 4 normal + it full combo; comboing off Fuwa + Sakitama is very funny. You can even get full combo with no normal if you 
open Sakitama + Aratama. Cutting Saki or Sayori for more non-engine/one less 'Brick' respectively is considerable but does remove some utility from the engine. 

The typical endboard of the deck consists of: Gigantic "Champion" Sargas  (bounce or pop when material is detached from anywhere), UDF or UFZ with Gung-ho attached (summons Springans Captain Sargas  from deck which is a detach from any xyz you control to pop a face-up card), Regulus Omni-Negate and either a searched Nib with possibly S:P or I:P if you play her or interluder Omni-Negate.
Post side, due to the archetype including machines, it is possible to side in a Secret Village of the Spellcasters  package through Planet Pathfinder via Gear Gigant X, turned on by Hiita. This can cheese some wins against spell heavy decks like Sky Striker and Mitsurugi and to a lesser extend Dracotail.

The deck can suffer from bricking sometimes due to having only a single 1 card combo and the 2 card combos, whilst plentiful, don't always line up; as well as a handful of engine requirements.
Its resilience to handtraps is fairly hand dependent; it can range from quite resilient to folding to a single ash or impulse (usually on Tally-ho!Springans).

This deck doesn't run a lot of spells, so it can play Anti-Spell Fragrance.

Use 1 card combos from either Yummy or Tri-Brigade which bridge into each other and act as extenders. The locks from main deck Tri-Brigades, Obedience Schooled or Tri-Brigade Arms Mouser are irrelevant in this deck because the full combos for each engine only uses beasts aside from the summon of Ancient Warrior's Oath - Double Dragon Lords. The standard endboard is a Yummy Synchro, Yummy Suprise, Tri-Brigade Revolt which revives Tri-Brigade Arms Mouser to flip a monster face-down and banishes 1 from Tri-Brigade Shuraig The Ominous Omen, and Tri-Brigade Ferrijit The Barren Blossom which will be sent to the gy as cost for Ancient Warrior's Oath Double Dragon Lords to fish for handtraps and return 1 card on the field to the hand.

deck_description: I just don't really enjoy the Yummy stuff anymore, so I would rather just do mitsurugi with this instead.

deck_excerpt: GMX is kool, and I love dinos, so here we are.
deck_description:
Definitely can play with the exact cards included here. I just went with Xeno stuff for lars. Jurrac stuff feels real good.

GMX is not good yet, but it might be with the next wave of support, so this is just preparing for that.

(Note: due to site restrictions, I had to use Evil Thorn and Necro Fleur as proxies for Vijam the Cubic seed. Please pretend that they are that card.)

I understand that part of the point of Domain is running all cards as one-ofs. That said, Cubics are a deck that do not function at all with this rule, or if they do, they end up as Crimson Nova turbo. Not to diss on that strategy or anything, but that particular playstyle doesn't really allow the other cards to shine, and instead, they're used to fulfill a cost rather than their intended purposes.

 

With all that said, I chose Vijam as my only duplicate card so as to keep with the intended playstyle as much as possible. Duza also was selected as a Deck Master so that I could tribute it to summon other Cubic cards if needed. As for the Lightsworns, they just do their own thing, and as they mill cards, they will occasionally send Cubic cards that benefit off of being sent to the graveyard. All of this may sound fine in theory, however, Cubics are a bricky mess of an archetype.

 

I'll work more on this deck once I overcome some burnout.

With it's recyclable trap negates, low point cost, slow control gameplay, 20+ staples and redundant consistency, Odion has become the format's #1 trap-based strategy!

Unleash your inner hero with a fast, explosive HERO strategy built to overwhelm the opponent from turn one.

This deck combines Elemental HERO, Destiny HERO, and Vision HERO monsters to give you constant access to powerful starters and extenders like Elemental HERO Stratos, Vision HERO Faris, and Vision HERO Vyon, so you can reliably set up your Fusion plays every game. With Destiny HERO – Malicious, Destiny HERO – Denier, and Fusion Destiny, you threaten Destiny HERO – Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer while still keeping access to classic HERO boss monsters such as Elemental HERO Sunrise, Elemental HERO Absolute Zero, and Elemental HERO Shining Neos Wingman.

Thanks to Mask Change and multiple Masked HERO Dark Law, you can pivot your combo into a brutal control plan that banishes your opponent’s key cards and shuts down graveyard strategies, all while pressuring their life points. Powerful spell support, including A Hero Lives, E – Emergency Call, Reinforcement of the Army, Polymerization, Miracle Fusion, and Favorite Contact, ensures you see your heroes early and often, turning almost any opening hand into a full Fusion board.

Backed by hand traps like Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and Maxx “C”, plus disruption from Infinite Impermanence, this list doesn’t just combo—it fights through opposing boards and protects your plays. The Extra Deck is rounded out with essential Xtra HERO links like Cross Crusader, Wonder Driver, Infernal Devicer, and Dread Decimator, giving you powerful link lines that recycle resources, extend plays, and push for a game in a single turn.

If you want a deck that feels like piloting a Saturday-morning superhero team—explosive, stylish, and always threatening lethal—this HERO build is ready to hit the table and steal the spotlight at your next event.

deck_excerpt: Because surely Fusion Trishula is an Ice Barrier card
deck_description:
With Herald of the Arc Light now banned, every Prediction Princess Deck that utilizes Mereologic Aggregator to send Herald from the Extra Deck to the GY does not work anymore. Is there any alternative to this? Sadly, for Prediction Princess, the answer is no. This Deck does not have a starter, nor does it have any consistency cards or any easily accessible searchers, which is why I’ve created so many Prediction Princess Decks to see which archetype you can splash into Prediction Princess in order to give it an engine to start its plays. I only have a few Prediction Princess Decks left to share, which I will be putting out as Theorycrafting Decks. However, this is sadly the end for Prediction Princess. Is the archetype still playable? Yes, but that is if you are running like Impcantations and Pre-Preperation of Rites. Heck, you can’t even Normal Summon Diviner of the Herald to send Arc Light anymore. o7

This is an Ice Barrier Prediction Princess Deck that I made to go along with a supposed guide on the best Synchro Monsters to make with Turbo-Tainted Hot Rod GT19 in Prediction Princess, but as long as Herald remains banned, that is never coming out. This Deck plays similarly to my /Assault Mode Prediction Princess Deck because the idea behind the Deck is playing a good number of 1-card starters that translate into a Level 9 monster and hoping to draw a Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag or World Legacy Monstrosity alongside it to go into Mereologic Aggregator to send Herald and do all of that stuff. I have to admit, one of Ice Barrier’s strengths is its consistency if you are intending to use Hexa Spirit of the Ice Barrier as your primary starter, but even 3 Medallion of the Ice Barrier alongside 3 Hexa Spirit to send Mirror Mage of the Ice Barrier from Deck to GY is good enough. 

Full combo is Hexa Spirit, Kaku, and a Prediction Princess card or Hexa Spirit and Monstrosity. Let’s say that we have Kaku and Tarotrei. Normal Summon Hexa Spirit of the Ice Barrier and activate its effect to send Mirror Mage of the Ice Barrier from Deck to GY, making its own Level become 2 for the rest of the turn. Mirror Mage’s effect triggers in the GY to add Georgius, Swordman of the Ice Barrier from Deck to hand. Because you control an Ice Barrier, you can Special Summon Georgius from hand, and on Summon, Georgius Special Summons Mirror Mage back from the GY. Banish Hexa Spirit, Georgius, and Mirror Mage in order to Special Summon Trishula, the Dragon of Icy Imprisonment from Extra Deck into the EMZ. Because there is a monster in the EMZ, you can activate Kaku in hand to Special Summon it. Xyz Kaku and Trishula into Mereologic Aggregator in the EMZ who sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY on Xyz Summon. Herald triggers in GY to add Underworld Ritual of Prediction from Deck to hand. Activate Aggregator’s other effect, targeting Herald in GY, detaching 1, and attaching Herald from GY to it. Link Aggregator into Gravity Controller. Herald triggers in GY again, adding Prediction Princess Tarotreith from Deck to hand. Activate Underworld Ritual to Ritual Summon Tarotrei by Tributing Tarotreith from hand. During the End Phase, Tarotrei activates to Special Summon Tarotreith from GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, you can banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon Bibliomuse from Deck face-down and you can Chain the effect of Tarotrei, targeting Tarotreith to flip it face-up. Tarotreith’s Flip Effect triggers to Special Summon Deus-X Krawler from your Deck face-down. And then on a new Chain, you can use Tarotreith’s other effect to flip Deus-X and Bibliomuse face-up. Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect searches for a Prediction Princess monster and a Ritual Spell from your Deck while also protecting your Rituals from being targeted or destroyed by your opponent’s card effects while it’s face-up on the field. Deus-X, after it has been flipped face-up, negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field.

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 2 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag which can Special Summon itself from hand if there is a monster in the EMZ. Also, you can target 1 face-up monster in the EMZ and equip that monster to Kaku, and if Kaku destroys a monster by battle, you can Special Summon a Monster Card that is equipped to it. I really like Kaku. 1 Turbo-Tainted Hot Rod GT19 which is a Level 3 Flip Tuner whose Flip Effect allows you to declare a Level from 1 to 9 and have it become that Level until the end of the turn. Also, after it has been flipped face-up, it can Quick Effect target 1 other face-up monster on either field to Quick Synchro with that monster, but you can only use 1 effect per turn and only once that turn. You don’t need to be playing this, which means that you can take out the Synchro Monsters that we are playing for Hot Rod in the Extra Deck also. 1 Georgius, Swordman of the Ice Barrier which you can Special Summon from hand if you control an Ice Barrier monster and if he is Normal or Special Summoned, you can Special Summon 1 Level 5 or lower Ice Barrier monster from hand or GY. No clue why this guy is called “swordman” and not “swordsman,” but he is just a really good monster in Ice Barrier in general since he can just Summon himself from hand and then Summon another Ice Barrier from either hand or GY. 2 Mirror Mage of the Ice Barrier which we are only using to add an Ice Barrier card from Deck or banishment to hand if it is sent to GY. You only need the 1 copy of Georgius because it is completely fine if you hard draw him. Its other effect locks you into WATER monsters only from the Extra Deck for the rest of the turn, so we can’t exactly use it. We are playing 2 Mirror Mage because Hexa Spirit only sends from Deck, and we would have no way of getting Mirror Mage out of our hand if we drew it, without also drawing Georgius. 3 Hexa Spirit of the Ice Barrier which can send a Level 3 or lower Ice Barrier monster from Deck to GY and make its Level become the same as the Level of the sent monster until the end of the turn. 3 Deep Sea Diva which can Special Summon a Level 3 or lower Sea Serpent from Deck on Normal Summon. Hexa Spirit is a Sea Serpent, which means that Normal Summoning Deep Sea Diva can get you straight to Hexa Spirit, giving you 3 additional copies of Hexa Spirit in Deck. For handtraps, we have 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, and 2 Droll & Lock Bird. 

For Spell/Traps: 3 Medallion of the Ice Barrier which adds an Ice Barrier monster from Deck to hand and it is not once per turn. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. 3 Infinite Impermanence.

Extra Deck: 1 Trishula, the Dragon of Icy Imprisonment. With the right hand, you could find a line to get from some Ice Barrier cards to a Level 9 Synchro Monster. However, we are playing Georgius, Mirror Mage, and Hexa Spirit as our Ice Barrier monsters in the Main Deck, as those are among the best Ice Barrier monster you could be playing, but they are also all Tuners, which means that you can’t exactly find a way to a Level 9 Synchro Monster with them. But, Fusion Trishula is technically an Ice Barrier monster, lore-wise that is. 1 Elder Entity N’tss, which can target and destroy a card on the field if it sent to the GY. For the Synchro Monsters that we are playing for Turbo-Tainted Hot Rod GT19, we have Snake-Eyes Vengeance Dragon, Juraishin, the Cursed Thunder God, Shooting Riser Dragon, and Toxic Boxfish. I don’t want to really go into detail about each of them since Hot Rod isn’t a card that you must play in this Deck. It’s only here because I was going to use this list as a part of a guide to using Hot Rod in Prediction Princess. If you don’t want to be playing Hot Rod, you can take out these Synchro Monsters for like an I:P Masquerena, Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder, and Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 1 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck to hand when it is sent to GY. The card is banned, so you can’t play it or this Deck. But this is just me showcasing this Deck in hopes that it will one day come back. 1 Galaxy-Eyes Antimatter Dragon, which is a Rank 9 Xyz Monster that can detach a material from itself to make up to 2 attacks on monsters during each Battle Phase this turn, and then if the detached material was a monster, you can send a monster with the same Type as it from your Deck to the GY. Also, if it would deal battle damage while it still has material, that battle damage is halved. For me, this card, as a Rank 9 in a Prediction Princess Deck, has similar usage to Infinitrack Earth Slicer, K9-X “Werewolf”, and K9-X “Ripper/Milennia”. They are all Rank 9 Xyz Monsters with over 3000 ATK who give the Deck some strong options during the Battle Phase and outside of the Battle Phase. Earth Slicer is a 3100 ATK monster who can detach any number of materials to target the same number of cards on the field and destroy them. Also, if it destroys a monster by battle, it can attach that monster to itself as material. Werewolf is a 3300 ATK monster who can attack a number of times up to the number of materials it has attached to it, and if your opponent activates a card or effect, it can Quick Effect detach a material to banish up to 1 card each from your opponent’s field and GY if it is currently your turn or look at your opponent’s hand and banish a card from it face-up until the End Phase if it is currently your opponent’s turn. Ripper/Milennia is a 3100 ATK monster with piercing who can Quick Effect detach 2 materials when your opponent activates a monster effect to negate the effect and destroy all cards on the field. Out of those 3, Ripper/Milennia is the worst one because it is a 3100 piercer who just has a panic button that nukes the entire board. Earth Slicer is the most proactive out of the 3 because it can detach any number of materials and destroy the same number of cards on the field. But, it can also attach monsters it destroys by battle to itself as material, preventing your opponent from bringing that monster back from GY or banishment later while also giving it material to destroy more cards on your next turn. Werewolf is a reactive card that mainly banishes up to 1 card each from your opponent’s field and/or GY, but it can make up to 2 attacks during the Battle Phase (given that it has 2 materials attached) while also having a 3300 ATK stat. Antimatter Dragon is a weird card. You can make it in Prediction Princess on Turn 3 or so in order to have a 4000 ATK beater who can declare up to 2 attacks on monsters. But, battle damage is halved if it still has material and you don’t really benefit from being able to send a monster with the same Type as the detached monster from Deck to GY. Unless you need a 4k beater who can attack 2 monsters, either Werewolf or Earth Slicer would be better picks for this role.  2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 Dyna Mondo. 1 Gravity Controller. 

Side Deck: 3 Dinowrestler Pankratops, 3 Mulcharmy Purulia, 2 Dark Ruler No More, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, 2 Triple Tactics Thrust, 1 Triple Tactics Talent, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: Making use of Herald's & Shadoll's aspects to play through boards, add interruption, or small card economy. Purrely ^W^
deck_description:
Current as of 1-27-2026 genesys purrely deck I have been playing.
Was thinking a lot against Kewl tune & onomat {kewl because more relvant and onmat because its on my nerves sometimes lol}, also techically you can also play a Mudora the Sword Oracle for 1 point as another fairy but didnt find situations yet where it felt impactful so far this format from my glances.

Sideboard talk then Purrely tips.

Branded in high spirits you can reveal a fairy then send Shaddolll construct to search Shaddoll Fusion going second. 

Shaddoll hedghog sometimes is just an enconomy card to let you keep a card in hand to discard for purrely spells. That I side in when going first game in games 2 or 3 without putting in shaddoll fusions. (Also i put it in going 2nd when adding fusions and high spirits against ED using deck.)                       It can not search itself**

GENERAL TIPS::

Sleepy memory is once per turn so if you expurreleap into noir on your monster you can use it again in the standbye on new chain.

Tarai can enable Hapiness OTKs going 2nd. (Its also a fairy for discarding off of Heralds) It also only summons on resolution for its effect & it activates in the hand. (so it gets around on field monster negation)

Gnomaterial is good against decks that need specifically names for their plays. Like for example going 2nd against kewl tune you can gnomaterial the Reco summoned off of Red Nova. Its bad in most other contexts since "controling no cards" is hard to fufill. 

Gordian slicer has "At the start of your Main Phase 1 or 2" restriction (kinda like pot of extravagance).

Expurrely Noir is better in game 1 then game 2 or 3 when your opponent likely has kaijus, kurikara, goblin biker's (to take level 1 purrely material making it no longer a quick effect), so its better to usually summon more epurrelys.

So sometimes doubling up on Epurrely Beauty or setting a purrely quick play spell to banish a monster with Epurrely Plump is better than a tributed noir.

The only HARD once per turns in the purrely engine is "+My Friend Purrely", "+Purrelyly", & "+Purreleap!?".

Kambi can be nice but realise its fairy lock for when you tribute it for its effect if your using it for going 2nd. (may be better to discard sometimes)

PURRELY OTK IF YOU DO NOT KNOW IT: with the combination of "+Epurrely Hapiness" & "+Purrely Delicious Memory" (or 2) you can OTK.

Using 2 of your thrice per turns to attach Purrely happy memory during the battlephase after you search with Happiness, your 3rd is often for 1 of the delicious memories you have activated.
You should get otk if the monster your attacking has 2800 or less atk (rember end of damage step to search also "you can" half the atk of 1 monster on the field. (& of course you dont get interupted with this small loop.)

deck_excerpt: To seto kaiba would play a pure blue eye deck
deck_description: A pure blue eyes deck seto kaiba would use

Predaplant has always been a good engine for enabling Prediction Princess, so I was really excited to see Predaplant Support coming out in BLZD, especially since it gives Predaplant a new Tuner and an extender. In general, the Predaplant Support from BLZD is great. But the real question is: “Is it good for enabling Predaplant Prediction Princess?” Surprisingly, no. Predaplant Longinephila, Predaplant Lilizard, and Predaplant Baalthea are crazy cards for the Deck. In fact, Longinephilia by itself does translate to an Ib the World Chalice Justiciar. It’s just that once you make Ib, there aren’t any good ways to then get to a Level 9 monster., and I am talking about this in context of a “Predaplant Prediction Princess Deck” and not a “Predaplant Runick Prediction Princess Deck”. Theoretically, this wouldn’t be an issue if we used Predaprimitive, another one of their new cards, but that locks you into Plant and Dragon monsters for the rest of the turn. So, this puts you back to using Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio as your starter to go into Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra. But if you then decide to include the new Predaplant Support with Scorpio and Cobra, the resulting Deck is worse than my previous Predaplant Prediction Princess list combo and set-up-wise while having a somewhat better endboard. I’ll be so real, I’d rather have a tighter and more consistent combo than a better endboard. Well, it doesn’t really matter anyways because Herald of the Arc Light is banned, but I’d rather play Predaplant Prediction Princess without the BLZD Support. Which is why, if you are going to use the new Predaplant Support from BLZD in Prediction Princess, it would be best to use it in Runick Prediction Princess. 

Full combo is Predaplant Longinephila and any Runick Quick-Play Spell, which we will say is Runick Tip for this example. Normal Summon Longinephila and activate its effect to search for Predaplant Lilizard. Because you control a Predaplant monster, you can Special Summon Lilizard from hand. Synchro Loneginephila and Lilizard into Predaplant Baalthea. Activate Baalthea’s effect on Synchro Summon to Special Summon Lilizard back from GY. Because Lilizard was Special Summoned from the GY, you can draw 1 card. Banish Longinephila from GY to activate its effect to place a Predator Counter on Lilizard, making it a Level 1 monster. Synchro Baalthea and Lilizard into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar who adds World Legacy Monstrosity from Deck to hand. Activate Runick Tip to Special Summon Sleipnir the Runick Mane from Extra Deck to the EMZ. Activate Monstrosity targeting Sleipnir to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Deus-X Krawler from Deck. Xyz Deus-X and Sleipnir into Mereologic Aggregator who sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY on Xyz Summon. Herald then triggers to add Prediction Princess Tarotrei from Deck to hand. Activate Aggregator’s other effect, targeting Herald in GY, and detaching 1 material to attach Herald from GY to itself. Link Aggregator and Ib into S:P Little Knight. Herald triggers again as it is sent to the GY again, which adds Underworld Ritual of Prediction from Deck to hand. Activate Underworld Ritual tributing Bibliomuse to Ritual Summon Tarotrei from hand. Bibliomuse triggers off of being tributed and Special Summons herself back from the GY face-down. Activate Tarotrei to flip Bibliomuse face-up and Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect adds Prediction Princess Tarotreith and another Underworld Ritual from Deck to hand. Activate the second Underworld Ritual, tributing Bibliomuse, to Ritual Summon Tarotreith face-down. During your End Phase, Tarotrei activates to Special Summon back Deus-X Krawler from GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, banish Underworld Ritual from your GY to Special Summon a Bibliomuse from your Deck face-down and chain Tarotrei’s effect to flip Tarotreith face-up. On a new chain, Tarotreith’s Flip Effect activates which Special Summons Summoner of Illusions from your Deck face-down. Tarotreith can then flip Bibliomuse, Deus-X, and Summoner of Illusions face-up. Bibliomuse searches for a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters cannot be targeted or destroyed by your opponent’s card effects. Deus-X negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field while it is face-up after being flipped. Summoner of Illusions’s mandatory Flip Effect then activates, tributing a monster you control to Special Summon either Starving Venom Wing Dragon or Invoked Caliga from Extra Deck. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Pot of the Forbidden which has a Flip Effect that lets you choose between Drawing 2 cards, returning all Spell/Traps on the field to the hand, destroying all monsters your opponent controls, or looking at your opponent's hand and shuffling a card from it back into the Deck. We are not playing PIXEA because it is a LIGHT and if we target Sleipnir with Monstrosity, we cannot Special Summon a LIGHT monster from Deck with Monstrosity. This can be remedied by Summoning Geri the Runick Fangs instead of Sleipnir the Runick Mane to have a Level 4 monster that can be Synchroed with Ib the World Chalice Justiciar to make a non-LIGHT Level 9 Synchro Monster. However, that means you will have to be ending on a Gravity Controller or have to use another Runick Spell to get out another Runick Monster to make S:P. It’s really up to you to choose which line you want to go through. 1 Summoner of Illusions whose Flip Effect is a mandatory effect activation when it is flipped face-up which tributes another monster you control to Special Summon a Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck, but that monster is destroyed during the End Phase of this turn. 3 Lonefire Blossom which can tribute a Plant to Special Summon a Plant from Deck. 1 Predaplant Lilizard. If you control a Predaplant or Starving Venom monster, you can Special Summon it from hand and then you can also add a Polymerization from Deck to hand. Its only other effect that we are using is its 3rd effect, which draws you a card if it is Special Summoned from the GY. If you really wanted to, you could play a copy of Polymerization just to have the option to make something like a Guardian Chimera. This card is not a brick by the way. If you hard draw it, there are no repercussions for that. 3 Predaplant Longinephila which adds a Predap card from Dec to hand except for itself if it is Normal or Special Summoned. Also, you can banish it from GY to either place a Predator Counter on a monster on the field (making it a Level 1 if it is Level 2 or higher while it has the Counter) or it sets a Polymerization from GY or banishment. 

For Spell/Traps: 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 1 Runick Fountain which allows us to activate Runick Quick-Play Spells from our hand during your opponent’s turn and if you activate a Runick Quick-Play Spell Card, you can target up to 3 Runick Quick-Play Spells in your GY and place them on the bottom of your Deck in any order and draw the same number of cards. For the Runick Quick-Play Spells: 3 Runick Tip, 2 Runick Flashing Fire, 3 Runick Slumber, 1 Runick Freezing Curses, 3 Runick Destruction, 1 Runick Dispelling, and 1 Runick Smiting Storm.Each of them allows you to choose between an effect that is unique to the card and an effect that Special Summons a Runick monster from your Extra Deck to the EMZ, but you are forced to skip your next Battle Phase. Tip searches for a Runick card from Deck before banishing the top card of your opponent’s Deck.  Flashing Fire targets and destroys a Special Summoned monster your opponent controls before banishing the top 2 cards of your opponent’s Deck. Slumber targets a face-up monster on the field and prevents it from being destroyed by battle or card effect the next instance it would be this turn, but it cannot attack and then you banish the top 3 cards of your opponent’s Deck. Freezing Curses targets and negate the effects of an Effect Monster your opponent controls until the end of the turn and banishes the top 3 cards of their Deck. Destruction targets and destroys a Spell/Trap your opponent controls and then banishes the top 4 cards of their Deck. Dispelling, if your opponent adds a card(s) from their Deck to their hand, discards a random card out of their hand and then banishes the top 2 cards of their Deck. Smiting Storm banishes cards from the top of your opponent’s Deck up to the number of cards they control. 1 Triple Tactics Talent. 1 Called by the Grave. 1 Instant Fusion which gets you Predaplant Ambulomelides who then gets you to Longinephila. 1 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. 1 World Legacy Pawns which allows you to target a face-down monster you control and then changes it to face-up Attack or Defense Position.

Extra Deck: 1 Starving Venom Wing Dragon and 1 Invoked Caliga as the SoI targets. Starving Venom Wing Dragon, if your opponent Special Summons a monster(s) face-up, can target 1 of them to gain ATK equal to that monster’s ATK until the end of the turn and also negate its effects until the end of the turn. Also, when another card or effect is activated on the field, it can Quick Effect destroy a card on the field. Lastly, if it is destroyed while in the Monster Zone, you can place it in your Pendulum Zone where its Pendulum Effect is that it places a Predator Counter on all monsters that are Special Summoned to your opponent’s field, turning them into Level 1 monsters if they are Level 2 or higher and have a Predator Counter on them. So, even if this card is destroyed by your opponent’s or destroyed during the End Phase because of SoI’s effect, you can still massively benefit from its Pendulum Effect. Caliga makes it so that while it is face-up on the field, each player can only attempt to activate 1 monster effect per turn and each player can only attack with 1 monster each Battle Phase. 1 Predaplant Ambulomelides which we can get off of Instant Fusion to then get to Longinephila. 1 Sleipnir the Runick Mane. 1 Hugin, the Runick Wings which adds a Runick Field Spell from your Deck to your hand on Special Summon and if another card(s) you control would be destroyed by card effect, you can banish her from field instead. 1 Wind Pegasus @Ignister. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar which searches for a World Legacy card on Synchro Summon. 1 Predaplant Baalthea which can Special Summon a Predaplant or Starving Venom monster from GY or face-up Extra Deck on Synchro Summon. 1 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand if it is sent to the GY. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Dyna Mondo and 1 S:P Little Knight.

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 2 Mulcharmy Purulia, 2 Lightning Storm, 2 Dark Ruler No More, and 3 Evenly Matched.

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.
