deck_excerpt: Bring your Tearlaments milling addiction into GENESYS format!
deck_description:
Although severly limited by the GENESYS points list with Scheiren and Kitkallos costing a whopping FIFTY POINTS apiece, (thus taking up this deck's entire points budget), Tearlaments is still an extremely powerful deck! Don't believe me? Check out my Youtube video below to see the deck in action! 

Experience the familiar dopamine high as you mill your entire deck to the graveyard, plussing a bazillion times like no tomorrow as you create an unbreakable board with the likes of Tearlaments Rulkallos (Summon negate), Tearlaments Cryme (Omni-negate shuffle), Tearlaments Sulliek (Monster negate), and Tearlaments Kaleidoheart (Target shuffle).

This strategy also has access to a large synchro suite due to millable tuners as well as the Lightsworn engine! Genex Return Zero (Monster negate destroy for each attribute), Draco Berserker of the Tenyi (Monster banish), Juraishin (Monster of spell field wide destruction), Chengying (Monster banish) and Wolfrayet (Shuffle all monsters your opponent controls). 

The main weakness of this deck is bricking and getting unlucky with mills. However, once the milling gets going, almost nothing stops Tearlaments from winning the game, especially in the lower power fomat of GENESYS! The combination of Scheiren, Kitkallos, TearKash and Scream mill 14 cards! The Lightsworn cards can also mill quite a bit as well, with both Minervas milling 7 cards and Weiss milling 2! It's often that after you end your turn, you may have only about 5-10 cards left in deck due to how much you mill, search and draw! 

Tearlaments in GENESYS functions as usual, milling as much as possible with the combined effort of the Tearlaments and Lightsworn cards. Make impenetrable boards going first and power through everything with immense amounts of milling going second with pure engine! Mill mill mill your way to victory!

And remember... TIARAMENTS STRONGEST~

(Shoutout to Lithium2300's Tearlament decklist and Youtube video for inspiring this deck!)

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: A symphony of Synchros set the stage!
deck_description:
The Nibiru-Resistant Medius Combo

Requires Medius the Pure + a spell or trap in your hand that you can set + Jet Synchron in your deck.

This combo resists Nibiru, the Primal Being by trading 1 monster for 1 token if your opponent activates its effect.

Step 1. Normal summon Medius the Pure.

Step 2. Activate Medius' effect to special summon an Elfnote Power Patron from your deck.

Step 3. Synchro summon Accel Synchron by using Medius and the Elfnote Power Patron as material. 

Step 4. Activate Elfnote Power Patron's graveyard effect to search for an Elfnote card. This combo will use Elfnote Tinia as the example. You'd generally search for her to extend your Elfnote plays.

Step 5. Activate Accel Synchron's effect to send Jet Synchron from your deck to your graveyard, then increase its level from 5 to 6.

Step 6. Special summon Elfnote Tinia to your center monster zone. This is your 4th summon.

Step 7. Activate Elfnotes Tinia's effect to place an Elfnotes: Welcome Home from your deck face-up on your field.

Step 8. Special summon Ultimaya Tzolkin by sending the level 6 Accel Synchron and Elfnote Tinia from your field to the graveyard. This is now your 5th summon. Your opponent must activate Nibiru, the Primal Being here or they'll likely miss their chance this turn.

Step 9. Set a spell or trap from your hand. This triggers Ultimaya Tzolkin's effect to special summon a Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon from your extra deck.

Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon can protect your board by negating and destroying the effect of Nibiru, the Primal Being. If your opponent activates Nibiru at Step 8 or 9 and tributes your Ultimaya Tzolkin, you can use that token as link material for Link Spider to continue your Elfnote plays. Elfnotes: Welcome Home can send the Link Spider from your field to your graveyard to special summon an Elfnote monster from your deck.

Some Tips

Keep your center monster zone clear for your Elfnote monsters.

Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon's effects aren't hard one-per-turn effects. Double the dragons is double the fun!

Elfnote Power Patron can search for an Elfnote spell or trap that you can set to trigger Ultimaya Tzolkin's effect.

Null Power Patron Realm - Vidria is an extender that can search for or special summon a Power Patron monster from your deck by revealing Junora the Power Patron of Tuning in your extra deck, then banishing a card from your hand face-down. Ancient Fairy Dragon can destroy Vidria to search for Secret Village of the Spellcasters.

Fidraulis Harmonia + any level 4 monster = Psychic End Punisher. Alternatively, base Accel Synchron + any level 6 = Psychic End Punisher.

Golden Cloud Beast - Malong is fodder for the effect of Fidraulis Harmonia. It's great for breaking boards. You'd destroy a monster with Fidraulis Harmonia then return a face-up card your opponent controls to the hand with Malong.

deck_excerpt: Let's leave them on a high note!
deck_description:
Some Tips

Medius the Pure + Elfnote Power Patron = Accel Synchron

Accel Synchron can boost or lower its level by 1 by sending Jet Synchron from your deck to the graveyard.

A level 6 Accel Synchron + a level 6 Elfnote monster = Ultimaya Tzolkin

Ultimaya Tzolkin can special summon a Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon from your extra deck when you set a spell or trap.

Shiranui Squiresaga is a level 7 synchro that you can summon under Dracotail's Secreterion Dragon lock, which prevents you from activating dragon and spellcaster monster effects. Shiranui Squiresaga's effect can banish herself to destroy Secreterion Dragon and 1 spell or trap your opponent controls.

Ancient Fairy Dragon can search for Secret Village of the Spellcasters by destroying a field spell on either player's field.

More info on the actual Springans side of the combo and what the new support does for the deck can be found here: https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/springans-685302 

The Fallen of the White Dragon engine is extremely strong in this deck, serving as extra ceiling for the endboard and a 1-card combo through itself and Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous summoning it from deck.

The combo can be just albaz summon ecclesia for Springans Merrymaker to combo if you want to play around handtraps more safely but the full combo is: normal albaz for ecclesia, make Ecclesia and the Dark Dragon to summon Guiding Quem, the Virtuous, send Tri-Brigade Springans Kitt to revive albaz and make Merrymaker to full combo. Springans so you can add Springans Branga off Tally-ho every time to search Springans Interluder and end on Merrymaker as the main endboard. Springans! and add Kitt to special to keep the Merrymaker for the endboard (as this would be what makes the Gallant Granite to search the Nibiru, the Primal Being) .

The endboard consists of: Gigantic "Champion" Sargas, UDF or UFZ with Gung-ho attached, synchro Ecclesia to summon Fallen of Albaz from deck for a Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon fusion, a searched Nib and interluder omni-negate.

deck_description:
How Do we make Dream mirror a solid deck atm. We turbo out Oneiros backed by hypnogogia, oneiromancy and phantasms which are all quite solid cards. After that we just play a ton of good generic cards which the deck can facilitate i.e. Chaos, Branded, Dogmatika, unchained and witchcrafter.

 

What does this deck do?

It actually has some quite fun/ intresting things going for it in a more casual setting (though not even really playable in lower powered formats like Genesys). It has some interruption and protection mostly in oneiromancy, Verre and the extra deck. Between Albaz, The Fallen & The virtuous, Unchained, Mirrorjade and the Vice madame- unchained Abomination - Oneiros shinnenigans the main selling point of this deck is that it can repeatedly eat and break entire boards given the circumstances where you get to a position where you can establish some level of end board prescence. 

 

Overall I don't think you can make much more of a dream mirror deck at the moment. You play enough dream mirror engine to get into Oneiros, your field spells and trap cards so you should really only play the number of dream mirror cards needed to get to that position then fill out the rest of the deck with options that can work with the dream mirror engine but does not directly compete with Neiroys normal summon slot and can compliment the dream mirror archetype and fix some of the issues with it. The deck is fun and very playable in a more relaxed casual setting but does not compete anywhere near any meta level

deck_excerpt: Dracotail Deck with Branded Engine for Burst Protocol Format
deck_description: With the new Banlist its time to finalize the List for the coming format.  If you have the luxury of time i'd reccomend waiting to let Fallen of the White Dragon and Ecclesia and the Dark Dragon come down in price, but if you are playing in tournaments you may not have that time (I for one don't, i've got a regional on release weekend).  I'd run 3 copies of Fallen of the White Dragon if it was only Treated as Albaz in Deck, field, Hand and GY like Shari Red, but its a Harpie Lady situation where its always treated as Albaz, including in Deck Building, and having one original Albaz lets you use Ecclesia and the Dark Dragon to summon it on the opponent's turn as interuption.  The Bystials let you use Starsource more efficiently by being higher level Darks, while having value into Mitsu and even against 1 card lines in the mirror by banishing Phyrxul.  I'm playing 2 and 2 with Urgula and Pan to make up for lost names with the limited Mululu, there is no real replacing the 2 Ketu (even though there should have been a Spell for Phyrxul with how the deck is structured otherwise).  You could definitely drop the second Pan for the third veiler in the side and then run something like Talent or Duster in the last Sideboard slot.  Titaniklad replaces Alba-Lenatus to give another way to get Cartesia from deck besides Ecclesia and the Dark Dragon.  You could also replace Spirit and Seal with more Branded Cards in the Extra, I just like having the Seals line available.  If you do so i'd reccomend replacing the second Pan with a Second Fallen and the Virtuous to get extra search targets for something the Dragon that Devours the Dogma.  Droll moves into the Side since I expect to see less Mitsu variants going around.  Overall this is a good shell of what Dracotail will look like going into the format.  Some will try to splash Majistus as well, i'm less excited about that variant since, while it has more Lukias access, it also has less room for non-engine, and i like my 3 faimena+ 13 Hand Trap setup.

1 Springans monster + Springans spell is your starting cards. (best one is Springans Rockey  and Springans Booty ) but can also discard a Springans spell/trap card in a bad hand. Usually good to go for Springans Merrymaker from field spell first.

Fallen of the White Dragon can be summoned from Gung-Ho! Springans! Detatch effect. (you cannot use its grave effect on the same turn)


Detatching  Gung-Ho! Springans!  from Gigantic "Champion" Sargas  on opponents turn with a set Tally-ho! Springans is ideal, to summon out Springans Captain Sargas for another interupt by detatching again. also try keep a Springans Brothers in your hand for albaz discard cost.

 Ecclesia and the Dark Dragon good to summon Guiding Quem, the Virtuous  on your turn if you have board space. 
Springans Interluder  is a good card going 1st , maybe an extra Springans Captain Sargas  is good after testing.

deck_excerpt: Same old as last year, with better starters
deck_description:
Thanks to Jade Dragon Mech, the Assault Mode package is now a one-card starter, and a pretty good one at that.

 

- Draw Phase, Emergency Teleport summon Psi-Reflector

- Psi-Reflector on summon search Assault Beast

- Standby/MP1, Assault Beast adds Assault Mode Activate

- Psi-Reflector reveal AMA, summon Assault Beast, modulate +4

- Synchro 9, Jade Dragon Mech, on summon eff send Tristaros

- Tristaros eff, pop Jade, summon Sulfador + Sulfefnir

- CL1 Sulfador dump Thystvern + Smiger, CL2 Jade banish Psi, target Sulfefnir to pop

- New chain, Sulfefnir summon Tristaros (2)

- Smiger add Inclusion, Inclusion add Cluster, Thystvern add Sulfador (2)

- Set Assault Mode Activate

- Sulfefnir in grave eff, discard Sulfador, summon then pop Assault Mode Activate

- Sulfador + Sulfefnir > Cyber Dragon Nova/Infinity

- Sulfador (GY) target Inclusion to summon, then Synchro Dawn Dragster

- Banish Inclusion to summon Tristaros

- Set Cluster

 

>>NOTE, if Drolled after Assault Beast, Sulfador dump Cluster + Inclusion instead, still pop Sulfefnir w/ Jade for Tristaros

- Synchro 7, Eleskeletus, on summon add Cluster

- Sulfador target Eleskeletus to summon

- Eleskeletus on pop summon Sulfefnir, Nova/Infinity

- Banish Inclusion to summon Tristaros, set Cluster, can hold AMA as fodder for Droplet/Super Poly

---

Nibiru should be Fuwalos, it's just there to make the deck look less expensive. Experimenting with Veilers though because having extra tuners in grave suddenly turns Jade Dragon Mech into a surprisingly scary board breaker.

deck_excerpt: Learn how to use GMX cards in the Dino deck.
deck_description:
The cards in the GMX archetype are interesting to use in the standard Dinosaur deck, as Konami has kept the focus for this archetype on Dinosaur Fusion Monsters.

 

This further improves upon the Dinosaur Fusion cards that have already been released over the years, such as Kaitoptera and Ground Xeno. One of the coolest things about this archetype is the possibility of recycling Miscellaneousaurus back from the banishment zone.

 

The most interesting thing about these cards is the fact that they are Level 8 Light and Dark attribute Fusion Monsters. This provides easy access to Rank-8 monsters, for example, Dragluxion to access Tachyon Transmigration, which is the counter trap for Galaxy-Eyes, a ridiculously strong counter trap because it negates all activated effects in the chain, returns the cards on the field to the deck, and can also be activated from the hand.

 

There are also other cards you can make, such as Number 38, or Dingirsu to protect your field from destruction effects. In a format where the best deck is Branded Dracotail, using the counter trap makes perfect sense because it negates all the effects of the infinite chain link that is made from a single Fusion Summon.

 

And since these cards bring more monster spam to the dinosaur's end board, you can always make A Bao A Qu, which is an excellent Link-4 that can extend your plays, pop opponent's cards, and be an excellent follow-up on the next turn.

I will demonstrate the test hands below in the 60-card version, which is very consistent with the addition of the GMX monsters.

 

Test Hands

Below I will show 1 test hand with Princess, and then the other 9 combos are all using A Bao on the end board. Put the continuation link in the duelingbook dot com /

 

Test Hand 1: (Promethean Princess version)

 

replay?id=813757-78547948

End Board: Tyranno + Phoenix + Dolkka + Velox /in GY: Miscellaneousaurus + Promethean Princess + GMX Researcher Selande /Banished: Omega

 

This combo is interesting and makes sense because the Researcher is a Fire attribute, but the fact that you're locked in while Princess is on the field takes away some of the synergy between the engines, since the deck is made up of monsters of different attributes. In this case, you would have to use Hiita in the extra deck as well.

I tested this version, and it's good considering it's more resilient against blind second cards like Dark Ruler No More, but I prefer the version with A Bao. Even the follow-ups with A Bao are better.

 

Test Hand 2: Miscellaneousaurus + Petiteranodon + Kimridge (A Bao version)

 

replay?id=813757-78551562

End Board: Dingirsu + A Bao + Dolkka + Velox /in GY: Miscellaneousaurus + Kimridge

 

The cool thing about this combo is that I managed to use Dugares to draw Ground Xeno and send it to the GY. With that, I was able to banish it and make Velox along with Dingirsu. This situation happens quite often.

Since I also drew Lost World, I activated it and managed to generate the token. It was convenient to bring Pankratops with the Pill to pop the token and bring Daneen from the deck to make the end board perfect.

 

Test Hand 3: Lithosagym + Petiteranodon + 1 Dino

 

replay?id=813757-78551255

End Board: Wyvern + Chimera + Dolkka + Tyranno + Linkuriboh + (Pankratops) /in GY: nothing

 

Here I set a spell to pop with the Wyvern's effect so as not to lose bodies on the board. Then I saw that it's possible to pass with Wyvern + Chimera on the field, and on the opponent's turn use Tyranno pop Chimera to trigger Wyvern's effect to bring Raptor from the deck and pop 1 opponent's card without targeting.

 

Test Hand 4: Archosaur + Petiteranodon + GMX Applied Experiment #55

 

replay?id=813757-78550619

End Board: Dingirsu + A Bao + Dolkka + Velox /in GY: Miscellaneousaurus + Kimridge

 

ERROR: Thinking Daneen is a GMX when using Experiment #55. It should have continued digging until it found a GMX.

This is where the cool interaction between A Bao and Kimridge comes in. You use A Bao to bring it out, return Misc to the whole deck, and use Velox to excavate Misc and add it to your hand.

 

Test Hand 5: Miscellaneousaurus + Babycerasaurus (Full Combo)

 

replay?id=813757-78548790

End Board: Dingirsu + A Bao + Dolkka + Velox /in GY: Miscellaneousaurus + Kimridge + Kaiju Slumber

 

In this combo I used Daneen for Fusion Summon and used a Dinosaur from my hand for the Fusion Summon of Velox. This way, I managed to keep Daneen's body on the field to perform A Bao and then Dingirsu.

Note: Don't forget that you will have to skip the Draw Phase on your return because of Dugares.

 

Test Hand 6: Oviraptor + Babycerasaurus (Full Combo)

 

replay?id=813757-78558937

End Board: Dingirsu + A Bao + Dolkka + Velox /in GY: Miscellaneousaurus + Kimridge

 

The cool thing about this end board is that you can use A Bao to bring Kimridge from the GY, activate its effect, and stack the top of the deck with Miscellaneousaurus.

Then you use Velox to dig up Miscellaneousaurus and add it to your hand, so you start your next turn with A Bao mulliganing, and have Miscellaneousaurus to protect the dinos in main phase 1.

 

Test Hand 7: Ground Xeno + Babycerasaurus (Scrap Raptor Combo)

 

replay?id=813757-78558138

End Board: Dingirsu + A Bao + Dolkka + Little Knight /in GY: Miscellaneousaurus

Can't access Daneen because you need to use the 3 Babycerasaurus first. But I was lucky with the draws with Dugares.

 

I could have done much better on this endboard if I had realized to use the Fusion Summon effect of Ground Xeno in the GY. Then I could have used Velox with Allos and Miscellaneousaurus.

And used A Bao to bring Allos back to then use Dingirsu.

Improved Endboard: Dingirsu + A Bao + Dolkka + Velox /in GY: Miscellaneousaurus

 

Test Hand 8: Miscellaneousaurus + Petiteranodon

 

replay?id=813757-78557672

Endboard: A Bao + Dolkka + Tyranno + Linkuriboh /in GY: nothing

 

Detail: this combo can be improved with Kaitoptera instead of Dogoran. I had removed it from the deck during testing, but I saw that in many hands you have to play pure Scrap Dino, since you can't access Daneen because the combo used Petiteranodon and not Babycerasaurus.

The difference here is that you would play Omega on the endboard to recycle Miscellaneousaurus; otherwise, the endboard would be the same.

 

Test Hand 9: Ground Xeno + Babycerasaurus (Scrap Raptor Combo)

 

replay?id=813757-78555451

End Board: A Bao + Dolkka + Tyranno + Linkuriboh /in GY: Kaiju Slumber

No luck with the draws with Dugares.

 

Test Hand 10

replay?id=813757-78577931

End Board: Lost World + Dingirsu + A Bao + Dolkka + Velox /in GY: Miscellaneousaurus

 

Decklist Choices

I like Knightmare Phoenix because I always want a quick answer to

continuous floodgates that, despite finally going to the banlist, you still get hit by from time to time.

 

But ideally you should switch to Knightmare Cerberus, which further increases the deck's 2-card combo combinations using Lost World, which is extremely necessary in a deck that needs to do 2-card combos to function.

 

Besides that, in this format I would use many other tech cards different from those presented, such as Evenly Matched against Dracotail, so this decklist can be further optimized.

 

It's nothing that makes this deck competitive, but at least it makes it decent for the current format.

Once again, creative liberty taken in order to fill a 40-card deck.

WCT-04's Water/Aqua archtype actually has potential, notably with Maiden of the Aqua granting the Umi boost (even tho its card description says otherwise) and the sheer amount of cards available, with good stats for that matter, plus the Legendary Ocean turning 5-star monsters into 4-starred, allowing them to be normal summoned without any tributes. This also makes Suijin a 6-star, thus, only requiring one tribute instead of two, but I felt it would be too big of a stretch to put that gimmick in Mako's Deck.

By the way, I did a few cutesy things: 1. Added "A Warrior Returning Alive", to symbolize Mako's dad returning (at least Mako wishes so) and 2. Added two Legendary Fishermen, him and his dad.

A sort of intresting Ritual deck centered around Demise, Ruin and the megalith rituals with the extra deck being relatively open with what you choose. For the purposes of this deck the extra deck is primarily centered on negates and destruction effects.

The deck itself is a bit bricky at times but can with the pot cards kind of cycle back your rituals from the GY meaning the deck has incredible and somewhat consistent burst potential. It fails to keep up with the modern meta game mostly due to the fact that it struggles to do anything outside of your turn with very limited interactions outside a few quick effects and quick play spells relying a lot on getting the value of your rituals on summon and mostly ending on quite generic extra deck end board pieces with maybe one or two of your rituals. The deck is however quite good at destruction and otks going second.

Fun deck to play casually but has a few to many weaknesses and issues to really be playable in more competetive settings.

A list I put together following the release of the Burst Protocol exosister support. The idea is that you don't need to invest points in to the spirit stuff and seventh tachyon can be used to search any exosister or goblindbergh depending on the situation. The test hands have proven capable. I really really like macro in this deck I think drawing it is just unbelievably strong especially in this format. I didnt include a side deck because I think it depends on the event and I havent come up with a single end-all side list that I would go with currently. Fun stuff. The onomat stuff has felt so good. Onomatokage's second effect is surprisngly dope in this strategy and adds a lot of grind game. If the points on onomatopaira are ever laxed in the future i would consider dropping the tachyon package to play gagaga girl and unbreakable xyz barrier bc i think that would be a bit more consistent and frankly better. All around i love this deck and the new support feels so unbelievably good to play. WIll attach a decklist video to this at some point. Enjoy :)

deck_name: Dark Magician Good Stuff (Fallen Primite Dark Magician)
deck_excerpt: All roads lead to the Dark Magician.
deck_description:
It's a pile of efficient dragon and spellcaster engines whose goals are to summon or support the Dark Magician. The Fallen engine in particular adds more dragons and spellcasters that the Dark Magician can fuse with.

Enlightenment Paladin serves as a bridge from your Fallen engine to your Dark Magician cards. If either player activates a spell card or effect during the turn you summon Enlightenment Paladin, then you can banish him to summon the Dark Magician of Destruction.

The Three Brave Swordsouls can search for Chronicle Sorceress. Chronicle Sorceress can send a Dark Magician or a card that mentions him from your deck to your graveyard. Send Magician Navigation to your graveyard for a face-up spell or trap negate on your opponent's turn if you control the Dark Magician.

You can also send a Dark Magician from your deck to your graveyard with the effect of Granguignol the Dusk Dragon.

Lastly, I'd play the new LOCH Dark Magician when he's released.

This variant of the Temple of the Kings deck attempts to simultaneously set up Naturia Exterio and Tyrant's Throes to create a difficult to break lock against Spells, Traps and the summoning of Effect Monsters. Meanwhile you can continue summoning the Apophis Trap Monsters (due to being treated as Normal Monsters) and revtrieve them from the GY with Divine Serpent Apophis unimpeded.

If you don't draw Tyrant's Throes, you're still likely to set up Naturia Exterio plus multiple monster negates via Apophis the Swamp Deity and Infinite Impermenance, as well as other interrupts / destructions.

In order to easily summon Mystical Beast of Serket to get to Naturia Exterio via Temple of the Kings, its best to summon The Man with the Mark using a Vernusylph monster to discard and then revive it to preserve your Normal Summon. You can also discard Mystical Beast of Serket and revive it the same way, or send it with Awakening Forests and revive it with another Vernusylph. Both maindeck Serket monsters can be searched by Misting Seedlings. Remember to summon Apophis the Serpent with Temple of the Kings before summoning Naturia Exterio.

You can also run Gallant Granite over Bagooska. In this instance, include Lord of the Heavenly Prison in the main deck (maybe swap it for one of the Tyrant's Throes). This is less permanent a lock but it lets you search Tyrant's Throes more easily and it only needs to be up for around 1 turn anyway.

deck_excerpt: MALISS IS FINALLY GONE... IT'S RUNICK TIME!
deck_description:
With the upcoming February 2026 banlist, Maliss is finally (mostly) phased out of ladder - meaning it's Runick's time to shine again! Let's dust off the Spright and Runick archetypes and prepare to dominate with one of the most potent control strategies of all time!

The ridiculously strong combination of Spright and Runick's smothering control and endless grind game create a deck that all strategies would have to fear and respect. Sprights ending on 3-5 interruptions (Red's monster negate, Carrot's S/T negate, Smasher's banish, and I:P Masquerena's quick link) combined with Runick's draw 3 and quick play spells generally stop any deck cold in their tracks. Both archetypes combined have a potential 10+ interruptions for your opponent to slog through, while maintaining a superior resource loop - outpacing most other strategies!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!


GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Summon Negates and burn baby burn
deck_description:
Key to the deck is to send a max metalmorph to the gy and summon metal Illusionist. Either turn it into a dragon (to get red-eyes) or if you have claws on field turn it into a warrior (to get flame swordsman). 

The Fullmetal dragon is a omni negate with a burn effect. Flame Swordsman is a continuous burn if your opponent uses effects and gains attack every time it burns. 

I prefer board breakers instead of HTs because the deck is focused around doing burn damage and having strong boys on field.
